{"title_page": "Rickard William Lloyd", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n|name        = Rickard William Lloyd\n|image       = \n|caption     = \n|birth_date  = {{Birth date|1859|03|17|df=yes}}\n|birth_place = [[Gibraltar]]\n|death_date  = {{Death date and age|1933|04|24|1859|03|17|df=yes}}\n|death_place = [[Kensington]], [[London]], England\n| education = [[Bedford Modern School]] \n| alma_mater = [[St Bartholomew's Hospital]]\n|other_names = \n|known_for   = [[Anesthesiologist|Anaesthetist]]<br>Author\n|occupation  = Consulting [[Anesthesiologist|Anaesthetist]]\n|nationality = United Kingdom\n}}\n\n'''Rickard William Lloyd''' [[Membership of the Royal College of Surgeons|MRCS]] LRCPEd (17 March 1859 \u2013 24 April 1933) was a Consulting [[Anesthesiologist|Anaesthetist]] and author.<ref name=\"auto\">''Who Was Who'', Published by A&C Black Limited, an imprint of Bloomsbury Publishing plc, 1920-2014; online edn, Oxford University Press, 2014; online edn, April 2014</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nLloyd was born in [[Gibraltar]]<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite journal|title=Dr. Rickard William Lloyd | pmc=2368701 | pmid=20777569|volume=1|year=1933|journal=Br Med J|pages=940|doi=10.1136/bmj.1.3777.940-b}}</ref> on 17 March 1859, the son of Major Edward Lloyd and the grandson of Sir Robert Stanford.<ref name=\"auto\"/> He was educated at [[Bedford Modern School]] and [[St Bartholomew's Hospital]], [[London]].<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n==Career==\nIn 1881 Lloyd served as a house-surgeon at the West London Hospital and [[St Mark's Hospital]], subsequently serving at both hospitals for over thirty years.  He was also House-Surgeon to St Peter's Hospital for Stone, an Anaesthetist at [[United Medical and Dental Schools of Guy's and St Thomas' Hospitals|Guy's Dental School]] and a former President of the West London Medico-Chirurgical Society.<ref name=\"auto\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=MLo1AQAAMAAJ&q=rickard+lloyd+physician&dq=rickard+lloyd+physician&hl=en&sa=X&ei=jvKPVbP1IcGTsgH0_JvgCg&ved=0CCAQ6AEwAA|title=The Lancet|work=google.co.uk}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?ei=avOPVZLvIcGMsAGVlojAAg&id=BSo1AQAAMAAJ&dq=rickard+lloyd+physician&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=rickard+lloyd|title=Burdett's Hospitals and Charities|work=google.co.uk}}</ref> On retiring in 1914 he was appointed Honorary Consulting Anaesthetist of the West London Hospital.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n==Authorship==\nLloyd was a contributor to various numerous journals, in particular the [[BMJ|British Medical Journal]].<ref name=\"auto\"/> He also took a particular interest in old paintings and was the author of 'The Cult of Old Paintings and the [[George Romney (painter)|Romney]] Case', which included a foreword by [[Edward Poynter|Sir Edward Poynter]].  In his foreword to the book [[Edward Poynter|Sir Edward Poynter]] says 'Rickard W Lloyd has set forth in an amusing and interesting way the difficulties that beset the cult of old paintings, to say nothing of the snares'.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldcat.org/title/cult-of-old-paintings-and-the-romney-case-huntington-v-lewis-and-simmons-relating-to-the-authenticity-of-a-picture-attributed-to-romney-illustrated-with-sixteen-plates/oclc/752471645&referer=brief_results|title=The Cult of Old Paintings and the Romney Case [Huntington V. Lewis and Simmons, relating to the authenticity of a picture attributed to Romney] ... Illustrated with sixteen plates.|work=worldcat.org}}</ref>\n\n==Family life==\nLloyd was unmarried and died in [[Kensington]], [[London]] on 24 April 1933.<ref name=\"auto\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ancestry.co.uk|title=Genealogy, Family Trees & Family History Records at Ancestry.co.uk|work=ancestry.co.uk}}</ref> His obituary was published in the British Medical Journal.<ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n\n==Selected works==\n* ''The Cult of Old Paintings and the Romney Case'', by Rickard W Lloyd, Published by Skeffington & Son Limited, 1917<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldcat.org/title/cult-of-old-paintings-and-the-romney-case/oclc/15510545&referer=brief_results|title=The cult of old paintings and the Romney case|work=worldcat.org}}</ref>\n* ''The Field View of the Anaesthetist''<ref>{{cite journal|title=THE FIELD OF VIEW OF THE ANAESTHETIST | pmc=2512847 | pages=401\u2013402 | volume=1 | issue=2198 | journal=Br Med J | doi=10.1136/bmj.1.2198.401-a}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n<references />\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lloyd, Rickard William}}\n[[Category:1859 births]]\n[[Category:1933 deaths]]\n[[Category:People educated at Bedford Modern School]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n|name        = Rickard William Lloyd\n|image       = \n|caption     = \n|birth_date  = {{Birth date|1859|03|17|df=yes}}\n|birth_place = [[Gibraltar]]\n|death_date  = {{Death date and age|1933|04|24|1859|03|17|df=yes}}\n|death_place = [[Kensington]], [[London]], England\n| education = [[Bedford Modern School]] \n| alma_mater = [[St Bartholomew's Hospital]]\n|other_names = \n|known_for   = [[Anesthesiologist|Anaesthetist]]<br>Author\n|occupation  = Consulting [[Anesthesiologist|Anaesthetist]]\n|nationality = United Kingdom\n}}\n\n'''Rickard William Lloyd''' [[Membership of the Royal College of Surgeons|MRCS]] LRCPEd (17 March 1859 \u2013 24 April 1933) was a Consulting [[Anesthesiologist|Anaesthetist]] and author.<ref name=\"auto\">''Who Was Who'', Published by A&C Black Limited, an imprint of Bloomsbury Publishing plc, 1920-2014; online edn, Oxford University Press, 2014; online edn, April 2014</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nLloyd was born in [[Gibraltar]]<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite journal|title=Dr. Rickard William Lloyd | pmc=2368701 | pmid=20777569|volume=1|year=1933|journal=Br Med J|pages=940|doi=10.1136/bmj.1.3777.940-b}}</ref> on 17 March 1859, the son of Major Edward Lloyd and the grandson of Sir Robert Stanford.<ref name=\"auto\"/> He was educated at [[Bedford Modern School]] and [[St Bartholomew's Hospital]], [[London]].<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n==Career==\nIn 1881 Lloyd served as a house-surgeon at the West London Hospital and [[St Mark's Hospital]], subsequently serving at both hospitals for over thirty years.  He was also House-Surgeon to St Peter's Hospital for Stone, an Anaesthetist at [[United Medical and Dental Schools of Guy's and St Thomas' Hospitals|Guy's Dental School]] and a former President of the West London Medico-Chirurgical Society.<ref name=\"auto\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=MLo1AQAAMAAJ&q=rickard+lloyd+physician&dq=rickard+lloyd+physician&hl=en&sa=X&ei=jvKPVbP1IcGTsgH0_JvgCg&ved=0CCAQ6AEwAA|title=The Lancet|work=google.co.uk}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?ei=avOPVZLvIcGMsAGVlojAAg&id=BSo1AQAAMAAJ&dq=rickard+lloyd+physician&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=rickard+lloyd|title=Burdett's Hospitals and Charities|work=google.co.uk}}</ref> On retiring in 1914 he was appointed Honorary Consulting Anaesthetist of the West London Hospital.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n==Authorship==\nLloyd was a contributor to various numerous journals, in particular the [[BMJ|British Medical Journal]].<ref name=\"auto\"/> He also took a particular interest in old paintings and was the author of 'The Cult of Old Paintings and the [[George Romney (painter)|Romney]] Case', which included a foreword by [[Edward Poynter|Sir Edward Poynter]].  In his foreword to the book [[Edward Poynter|Sir Edward Poynter]] says 'Rickard W Lloyd has set forth in an amusing and interesting way the difficulties that beset the cult of old paintings, to say nothing of the snares'.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldcat.org/title/cult-of-old-paintings-and-the-romney-case-huntington-v-lewis-and-simmons-relating-to-the-authenticity-of-a-picture-attributed-to-romney-illustrated-with-sixteen-plates/oclc/752471645&referer=brief_results|title=The Cult of Old Paintings and the Romney Case [Huntington V. Lewis and Simmons, relating to the authenticity of a picture attributed to Romney] ... Illustrated with sixteen plates.|work=worldcat.org}}</ref>\n\n==Family life==\nLloyd was unmarried and died in [[Kensington]], [[London]] on 24 April 1933.<ref name=\"auto\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ancestry.co.uk|title=Genealogy, Family Trees & Family History Records at Ancestry.co.uk|work=ancestry.co.uk}}</ref> His obituary was published in the British Medical Journal.<ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n\n==Selected works==\n* ''The Cult of Old Paintings and the Romney Case'', by Rickard W Lloyd, Published by Skeffington & Son Limited, 1917<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldcat.org/title/cult-of-old-paintings-and-the-romney-case/oclc/15510545&referer=brief_results|title=The cult of old paintings and the Romney case|work=worldcat.org}}</ref>\n* ''The Field View of the Anaesthetist''<ref>{{cite journal|title=THE FIELD OF VIEW OF THE ANAESTHETIST | pmc=2512847 | pages=401\u2013402 | volume=1 | issue=2198 | journal=Br Med J | doi=10.1136/bmj.1.2198.401-a}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n<references />\n<!--- After listing your sources please cite them using inline citations and place them after the information they cite. Please see http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:REFB for instructions on how to add citations. --->\n*\n*\n*\n*\n\n<!--- STOP! Be warned that by using this process instead of Articles for Creation, this article is subject to scrutiny. As an article in \"mainspace\", it will be DELETED if there are problems, not just declined. If you wish to use AfC, please return to the Wizard and continue from there. --->\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lloyd, Rickard William}}\n[[Category:1859 births]]\n[[Category:1933 deaths]]\n[[Category:People educated at Bedford Modern School]]\n", "name_user": "AlexdeGrey", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rickard_William_Lloyd"}
{"title_page": "Color difference", "text_new": "The '''difference''' or '''distance''' between two colors is a [[metric (mathematics)|metric]] of interest in [[color science]]. It allows quantified examination of a notion that formerly could only be described with adjectives. Quantification of these properties is of great importance to those whose work is color-critical. Common definitions make use of the [[Euclidean distance]] in a [[device independent]] [[color space]].\n\n==Euclidean==\nAs most definitions of color difference are distances within a [[color space]], the standard means of determining distances is the Euclidean distance. If one presently has an RGB (Red, Green, Blue) tuple and wishes to find the color difference, computationally one of the easiest is to call R, G, B linear dimensions defining the color space.\n\n:<math>\\mathrm{distance} = \\sqrt{ (R_2-R_1)^2+(G_2-G_1)^2 + (B_2-B_1)^2 }</math>\n\nWhen the result should be computationally simple as well, it is often acceptable to remove the square root and simply use:\n\n:<math>\\mathrm{distance}^2 = { (R_2-R_1)^2+(G_2-G_1)^2 + (B_2-B_1)^2 }</math>\n\nThis will work in cases when a single color is to be compared to a single color and the need is to simply know whether a distance is greater. If these squared color distances are summed, such a metric effectively becomes the [[variance]] of the color distances.\n\nThere have been many attempts to weight RGB values to better fit human perception, where the components are commonly weighted (red 30%, green 59%, and blue 11%), however these are demonstrably worse at color determinations and are properly the contributions to the brightness of these colors, rather than to the degree to which human vision has less tolerance for these colors. The closer approximations would be more properly:<ref name=euc/>\n:<math>\\begin{cases}\\sqrt{ 2 \\times \\Delta R^2 + 4 \\times \\Delta G^2 + 3 \\times \\Delta B^2 } & \\bar R < 128, \\\\\n\\sqrt{ 3 \\times \\Delta R^2 + 4 \\times \\Delta G^2 + 2 \\times \\Delta B^2 } & otherwise\\end{cases}</math>, \n\nOne of the better low-cost approximations (using a color range of 0&ndash;255) combines the two cases smoothly:<ref name=euc>{{Cite web | url=http://www.compuphase.com/cmetric.htm |title = Colour metric}}</ref>\n\n:<math>\\bar r = {{C_{1,R}  + C_{2,R} } \\over 2}</math>\n:<math>\\Delta C = \\sqrt {\\left( {2 + {{\\bar r} \\over {256}}} \\right) \\times \\Delta R^2  + 4 \\times \\Delta G^2  + \\left( {2 + {{255 - \\bar r} \\over {256}}} \\right) \\times \\Delta B^2 }</math>\n\nThere are a number of color distance formulae that attempt to use color spaces like HSV with the hue as a circle, placing the various colors within a three dimensional space of either a cylinder or cone, but most of these are just modifications of RGB; without accounting for differences in human color perception they will tend to be on par with a simple Euclidean metric.\n\n==CIELAB \u0394E*==\nThe [[International Commission on Illumination]] (CIE) calls their distance metric {{math|\u0394''E''<sup>*</sup><sub>''ab''</sub>}} (also called {{math|\u0394''E*''}}, or, inaccurately, {{math|''dE''*}}, {{mvar|dE}}, or \"Delta E\") where [[delta (letter)|delta]] is a [[Greek letter]] often used to denote difference, and '''E''' stands for ''Empfindung''; German for \"sensation\". Use of this term can be traced back to [[Hermann von Helmholtz]] and [[Ewald Hering]].<ref name=\"google\">{{cite book|title=Color Vision: Perspectives from Different Disciplines|last1=Backhaus |first1=W. |last2=Kliegl |first2=R. |last3=Werner |first3=J. S. |date=1998 |publisher=Walter de Gruyter |isbn=9783110154313 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DrduOSrOFegC&pg=PA188&lpg=PA188 |page=188 |accessdate=2014-12-02}}</ref><ref name=\"google2\">{{cite book |title=Light Vision Color |last=Valberg |first=A. |date=2005|publisher=Wiley |isbn=9780470849026 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OoESifAi9ZsC |page=278 |accessdate=2014-12-02}}</ref>\n\nPerceptual non-uniformities in the underlying [[CIELAB]] color space have led to the CIE refining their definition over the years, leading to the superior (as recommended by the CIE) 1994 and 2000 formulas.<ref>Real World Color Management, Second Edition (Bruce Fraser)</ref> These non-uniformities are important because [[Color vision#Physiology of color perception|the human eye is more sensitive to certain colors than others]]. A good metric should take this into account in order for the notion of a \"[[just noticeable difference]]\" to have meaning. Otherwise, a certain {{math|\u0394''E''}} may be insignificant between two colors in one part of the color space while being significant in some other part.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20080705054344/http://www.aim-dtp.net/aim/evaluation/cie_de/index.htm Evaluation of the CIE Color Difference Formulas]</ref>\n\n===CIE76===\nThe 1976 formula is the first formula that related a measured color difference to a known set of CIELAB coordinates. This formula has been succeeded by the 1994 and 2000 formulas because the CIELAB space turned out to be not as perceptually uniform as intended, especially in the saturated regions. This means that this formula rates these colors too highly as opposed to other colors.\n\nGiven two colors in [[CIELAB color space]], <math>({L^*_1},{a^*_1},{b^*_1})</math> and <math>({L^*_2},{a^*_2},{b^*_2})</math>, the CIE76 color difference formula is defined as:\n\n:<math>\\Delta E_{ab}^* = \\sqrt{ (L^*_2-L^*_1)^2+(a^*_2-a^*_1)^2 + (b^*_2-b^*_1)^2 }</math>.\n\n<math>\\Delta E_{ab}^* \\approx 2.3</math> corresponds to a [[JND]] (just noticeable difference).<ref>{{cite book|publisher=[[CRC Press]] |title=Digital Color Imaging Handbook |year=2003 |first=Gaurav |last=Sharma |isbn=0-8493-0900-X|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OxlBqY67rl0C&pg=PA31&vq=1.42&dq=jnd+gaurav+sharma|edition=1.7.2}}</ref>\n\n===CIE94===\nThe 1976 definition was extended to address perceptual non-uniformities, while retaining the CIELAB color space, by the introduction of application-specific weights derived from an automotive paint test's tolerance data.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.colorwiki.com/wiki/Delta_E:_The_Color_Difference |title=Delta E: The Color Difference |publisher=Colorwiki.com |accessdate=2009-04-16}}</ref>\n\n\u0394''E'' (1994) is defined in the [[colorfulness#Chroma|L*C*h* color space]] with differences in lightness, chroma and hue calculated from [[CIELAB|L*a*b* coordinates]]. Given a reference color<ref>Called such because the operator is not [[commutative]]. This makes it a [[quasimetric]].</ref> <math>(L^*_1,a^*_1,b^*_1)</math> and another color <math>(L^*_2,a^*_2,b^*_2)</math>, the difference is:<ref>{{cite web|first=Bruce Justin |last=Lindbloom |url=http://www.brucelindbloom.com/Eqn_DeltaE_CIE94.html |title=Delta E (CIE 1994) |publisher=Brucelindbloom.com |accessdate=2011-03-23}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.colorpro.com/info/software/heggie.html |title=Colour Difference Software by David Heggie |publisher=Colorpro.com |date=1995-12-19 |accessdate=2009-04-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite report |title=Colorimetry - Part 4: CIE 1976 L*a*b* Colour Space |series=Draft Standard |publisher=CIE |id=CIE DS 014-4.3/E:2007 |date=2007}}</ref>\n\n:<math>\\Delta E_{94}^* = \\sqrt{ \\left(\\frac{\\Delta L^*}{k_L S_L}\\right)^2 + \\left(\\frac{\\Delta C^*_{ab}}{k_C S_C}\\right)^2 + \\left(\\frac{\\Delta H^*_{ab}}{k_H S_H}\\right)^2 }</math>\n\nwhere:\n\n:<math>\\Delta L^* = L^*_1 - L^*_2</math>\n:<math>C^*_1 = \\sqrt{ {a^*_1}^2 + {b^*_1}^2 }</math>\n:<math>C^*_2 = \\sqrt{ {a^*_2}^2 + {b^*_2}^2 }</math>\n:<math>\\Delta C^*_{ab} = C^*_1 - C^*_2</math>\n:<math>\\Delta H^*_{ab} = \\sqrt{ {\\Delta E^*_{ab}}^2 - {\\Delta L^*}^2 - {\\Delta C^*_{ab}}^2 } = \\sqrt{ {\\Delta a^*}^2 + {\\Delta b^*}^2 - {\\Delta C^*_{ab}}^2 }</math>\n:<math>\\Delta a^* = a^*_1 - a^*_2</math>\n:<math>\\Delta b^* = b^*_1 - b^*_2</math>\n:<math>S_L = 1</math>\n:<math>S_C = 1+K_1 C^*_1</math>\n:<math>S_H = 1+K_2 C^*_1</math>\n\nand where ''k<sub>C</sub>'' and ''k<sub>H</sub>'' are usually both unity and the weighting factors ''k<sub>L</sub>'', ''K''<sub>1</sub> and ''K''<sub>2</sub> depend on the application:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" border=\"1\"\n|-\n!\n! graphic arts\n! textiles\n|-\n| <math>k_L</math>\n| 1\n| 2\n|-\n| <math>K_1</math>\n| 0.045\n| 0.048\n|-\n| <math>K_2</math>\n| 0.015\n| 0.014\n|}\n\nGeometrically, the quantity <math>\\Delta H^*_{ab}</math> corresponds to the arithmetic mean of the chord lengths of the equal chroma circles of the two colors.<ref>{{cite book |first=Georg A. |last=Klein |title=Industrial Color Physics |page=147 |isbn=978-1-4419-1196-4|date=2010-05-18 }}</ref>\n\n===CIEDE2000===\nSince the 1994 definition did not adequately resolve the [[perceptual uniformity]] issue, the CIE refined their definition, adding five corrections:<ref>{{cite journal|title=The CIEDE2000 color-difference formula: Implementation notes, supplementary test data, and mathematical observations |journal=Color Research & Applications |publisher=[[Wiley Interscience]] |first=Gaurav |last=Sharma |first2=Wencheng |last2=Wu |first3=Edul N. |last3=Dalal |volume=30 |issue=1 |pages=21\u201330 |doi=10.1002/col.20070 |url=http://www.ece.rochester.edu/~gsharma/ciede2000/ciede2000noteCRNA.pdf |year=2005 |ref=CITEREFSharma2005 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Bruce Justin |last=Lindbloom |url=http://www.brucelindbloom.com/Eqn_DeltaE_CIE2000.html |title=Delta E (CIE 2000) |publisher=Brucelindbloom.com |accessdate=2009-04-16}}</ref>\n* A hue rotation term (R<sub>T</sub>), to deal with the problematic blue region (hue angles in the neighborhood of 275\u00b0):<ref>[http://www.brucelindbloom.com/MunsellCalcHelp.html#BluePurple The \"Blue Turns Purple\" Problem], Bruce Lindbloom</ref>\n* Compensation for neutral colors (the primed values in the L*C*h differences)\n* Compensation for lightness (S<sub>L</sub>)\n* Compensation for chroma (S<sub>C</sub>)\n* Compensation for hue (S<sub>H</sub>)\n\n:<math>\\Delta E_{00}^* = \\sqrt{ \\left(\\frac{\\Delta L'}{k_L S_L}\\right)^2 + \\left(\\frac{\\Delta C'}{k_C S_C}\\right)^2 + \\left(\\frac{\\Delta H'}{k_H S_H}\\right)^2 + R_T \\frac{\\Delta C'}{k_C S_C}\\frac{\\Delta H'}{k_H S_H} }</math>\n\n::<small>'''Note:''' The formulae below should use degrees rather than radians; the issue is significant for ''R<sub>T</sub>''.</small>\n::<small>The ''k<sub>L</sub>'', ''k<sub>C</sub>'', and ''k<sub>H</sub>'' are usually unity.</small>\n\n:<math>\\Delta L^\\prime = L^*_2 - L^*_1</math>\n\n:<math>\\bar{L}^\\prime = \\frac{L^*_1 + L^*_2}{2} \\quad \\bar{C} = \\frac{C^*_1 + C^*_2}{2}</math>\n\n:<math>\n  a_1^\\prime = a_1^* + \\frac{a_1^*}{2} \\left( 1 - \\sqrt{\\frac{\\bar{C}^7}{\\bar{C}^7 + 25^7}} \\right) \\quad\n  a_2^\\prime = a_2^* + \\frac{a_2^*}{2} \\left( 1 - \\sqrt{\\frac{\\bar{C}^7}{\\bar{C}^7 + 25^7}} \\right)\n</math>\n\n:<math>\n  \\bar{C}^\\prime = \\frac{C_1^\\prime + C_2^\\prime}{2} \\mbox{ and }\n  \\Delta{C'}=C'_2-C'_1 \\quad\n  \\mbox{where }\n    C_1^\\prime = \\sqrt{a_1^{'^2} + b_1^{*^2}} \\quad\n    C_2^\\prime = \\sqrt{a_2^{'^2} + b_2^{*^2}} \\quad\n</math>\n\n:<math>\n  h_1^\\prime=\\text{atan2} (b_1^*, a_1^\\prime) \\mod 360^\\circ, \\quad\n  h_2^\\prime=\\text{atan2} (b_2^*, a_2^\\prime) \\mod 360^\\circ\n</math>\n:: <small>'''Note:''' The inverse tangent (tan<sup>&minus;1</sup>) can be computed using a common library routine <code>atan2(b, a&prime;)</code> which usually has a range from &minus;&pi; to &pi; radians; color specifications are given in 0 to 360 degrees, so some adjustment is needed. The inverse tangent is indeterminate if both ''a&prime;'' and ''b'' are zero (which also means that the corresponding ''C&prime;'' is zero); in that case, set the hue angle to zero. See {{harvnb|Sharma|2005|loc=eqn. 7}}.</small>\n\n:<math>\n  \\Delta h' = \\begin{cases}\n    h_2^\\prime - h_1^\\prime & \\left| h_1^\\prime - h_2^\\prime \\right| \\leq 180^\\circ \\\\\n    h_2^\\prime - h_1^\\prime + 360^\\circ & \\left| h_1^\\prime - h_2^\\prime \\right| > 180^\\circ, h_2^\\prime \\leq h_1^\\prime \\\\\n    h_2^\\prime - h_1^\\prime - 360^\\circ & \\left| h_1^\\prime - h_2^\\prime \\right| > 180^\\circ, h_2^\\prime > h_1^\\prime\n  \\end{cases}\n</math>\n:: <small>'''Note:''' When either ''C&prime;''<sub>1</sub> or ''C&prime;''<sub>2</sub> is zero, then &Delta;h&prime; is irrelevant and may be set to zero. See {{harvnb|Sharma|2005|loc=eqn. 10}}.</small>\n\n:<math>\n  \\Delta H^\\prime = 2 \\sqrt{C_1^\\prime C_2^\\prime} \\sin (\\Delta h^\\prime/2), \\quad \\bar{H}^\\prime=\\begin{cases}\n    (h_1^\\prime + h_2^\\prime)/2 & \\left| h_1^\\prime - h_2^\\prime \\right| \\leq 180^\\circ \\\\\n    (h_1^\\prime + h_2^\\prime + 360^\\circ)/2 & \\left| h_1^\\prime - h_2^\\prime \\right| > 180^\\circ, h_1^\\prime + h_2^\\prime < 360^\\circ \\\\\n    (h_1^\\prime + h_2^\\prime - 360^\\circ)/2 & \\left| h_1^\\prime - h_2^\\prime \\right| > 180^\\circ, h_1^\\prime + h_2^\\prime \\geq 360^\\circ \n    \\end{cases}\n</math>\n:: <small>'''Note:''' When either ''C&prime;''<sub>1</sub> or ''C&prime;''<sub>2</sub> is zero, then {{overbar|H}}&prime; is ''h&prime;''<sub>1</sub>+''h&prime;''<sub>2</sub> (no divide by 2; essentially, if one angle is indeterminate, then use the other angle as the average; relies on indeterminate angle being set to zero). See {{harvnb|Sharma|2005|loc=eqn. 7 and p. 23}} stating most implementations on the internet at the time had \"an error in the computation of average hue\".</small>\n\n:<math>\n  T = 1 - 0.17 \\cos ( \\bar{H}^\\prime - 30^\\circ )\n        + 0.24 \\cos (2\\bar{H}^\\prime)\n        + 0.32 \\cos (3\\bar{H}^\\prime + 6^\\circ )\n        - 0.20 \\cos (4\\bar{H}^\\prime - 63^\\circ)\n</math>\n\n:<math>\n  S_L = 1 + \\frac{0.015 \\left( \\bar{L}^\\prime - 50 \\right)^2}{\\sqrt{20 + {\\left(\\bar{L}^\\prime - 50 \\right)}^2} } \\quad\n  S_C = 1+0.045 \\bar{C}^\\prime \\quad\n  S_H = 1+0.015 \\bar{C}^\\prime T\n</math>\n\n:<math>R_T = -2 \\sqrt{\\frac{\\bar{C}'^7}{\\bar{C}'^7+25^7}} \\sin \\left[ 60^\\circ \\cdot \\exp \\left( -\\left[ \\frac{\\bar{H}'-275^\\circ}{25^\\circ} \\right]^2 \\right) \\right]</math>\n\n===CMC l:c (1984)===\nIn 1984, the Colour Measurement Committee of the [[Society of Dyers and Colourists]] defined a difference measure, also based on the L*C*h color model. Named after the developing committee, their metric is called '''CMC l:c'''. The [[quasimetric]] has two parameters: lightness (l) and chroma (c), allowing the users to weight the difference based on the ratio of l:c that is deemed appropriate for the application. Commonly used values are 2:1<ref>Meaning that the lightness contributes ''half'' as much to the difference (or, identically, is allowed ''twice'' the tolerance) as the chroma</ref> for acceptability and 1:1 for the threshold of imperceptibility.\n\nThe distance of a color <math>(L^*_2,C^*_2,h_2)</math> to a reference <math>(L^*_1,C^*_1,h_1)</math> is:<ref>{{cite web|first=Bruce Justin |last=Lindbloom |url=http://www.brucelindbloom.com/Eqn_DeltaE_CMC.html |title=Delta E (CMC) |publisher=Brucelindbloom.com |accessdate=2009-04-16}}</ref>\n\n: <math>\\Delta E^*_{CMC} = \\sqrt{ \\left( \\frac{L^*_2-L^*_1}{l S_L} \\right)^2 + \\left( \\frac{C^*_2-C^*_1}{c S_C} \\right)^2 + \\left( \\frac{\\Delta H^*_{ab}}{S_H} \\right)^2 }</math>\n\n: <math>S_L=\\begin{cases} 0.511 & L^*_1 < 16 \\\\ \\frac{0.040975 L^*_1}{1+0.01765 L^*_1} & L^*_1 \\geq 16 \\end{cases} \\quad S_C=\\frac{0.0638 C^*_1}{1+0.0131 C^*_1} + 0.638 \\quad S_H=S_C (FT+1-F)</math>\n\n: <math>F = \\sqrt{\\frac{C^{*^4}_1}{C^{*^4}_1+1900}} \\quad T=\\begin{cases} 0.56 + |0.2 \\cos (h_1+168^\\circ)| & 164^\\circ \\leq h_1 \\leq 345^\\circ \\\\ 0.36 + |0.4 \\cos (h_1+35^\\circ) | & \\mbox{otherwise} \\end{cases}</math>\n\nCMC l:c is designed to be used with [[CIE Standard Illuminant D65|D65]] and the [[CIE 1931 color space#CIE standard observer|CIE Supplementary Observer]].<ref>{{cite journal| url=http://www.hunterlab.com/appnotes/an10_96ar.pdf| title=CMC| journal=Insight on Color| volume=8| issue=13| date=1-15 October 1996| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060312161957/http://www.hunterlab.com/appnotes/an10_96ar.pdf| archive-date=2006-03-12}}</ref> The formula is not a metric but rather a quasimetric because it violates symmetry, parameter T is based on the hue of the <math>h_1</math> alone. This reference color means that the color difference from the first color to the second color is different than the color distance from the second color is to the first.\n\n===Tolerance===\n[[Image:CIExy1931 MacAdam.png|250px|right|thumb|A MacAdam diagram in the [[CIE 1931 color space]]. The ellipses are shown ten times their actual size.]]\n\n'''Tolerancing''' concerns the question \"What is a set of colors that are imperceptibly/acceptably close to a given reference?\" If the distance measure is '''''perceptually uniform''''', then the answer is simply \"the set of points whose distance to the reference is less than the just-noticeable-difference (JND) threshold.\" This requires a perceptually uniform metric in order for the threshold to be constant throughout the [[gamut]] (range of colors). Otherwise, the threshold will be a function of the reference color\u2014cumbersome as a practical guide.\n\nIn the [[CIE 1931 color space]], for example, the tolerance contours are defined by the [[MacAdam ellipse]], which holds L* (lightness) fixed. As can be observed on the adjacent diagram, the [[ellipse]]s denoting the tolerance contours vary in size. It is partly this non-uniformity that led to the creation of [[CIELUV]] and [[CIELAB]].\n\nMore generally, if the lightness is allowed to vary, then we find the tolerance set to be [[ellipsoid]]al. Increasing the weighting factor in the aforementioned distance expressions has the effect of increasing the size of the ellipsoid along the respective axis.<ref name=\"xrite\">{{cite web|url=http://www.xrite.com/documents/literature/en/L10-024_Color_Tolerance_en.pdf|date=14 January 1998|author=Susan Hughes|title=A guide to Understanding Color Tolerancing|accessdate=2014-12-02|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151010064956/http://www.xrite.com/documents/literature/en/L10-024_Color_Tolerance_en.pdf|archivedate=10 October 2015}}</ref>\n\n<!-- A diagram would handily illustrate the last paragraph. I am not going to post a {{reqdiagram}} tag here in order not to make the article ugly, but you can contribute if you like. -->\n\n{{clear}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[CIELAB]]\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite journal|title=Historical development of CIE recommended color difference equations|first=Alan R.|last=Robertson|journal=Color Research & Application|year=1990|volume=15|issue=3|pages=167\u2013170|doi=10.1002/col.5080150308|url=http://www3.interscience.wiley.com/cgi-bin/fulltext/114184816/PDFSTART}}{{dead link|date=February 2019|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}\n* {{cite journal|title=Uniformity of some recent color metrics tested with an accurate color-difference tolerance dataset |first=M. |last=Melgosa |last2=Quesada |first2=J. J. |last3=Hita |first3=E.|date=December 1994|journal=[[Applied Optics]]|volume=33|issue=34|pages=8069\u20138077|doi=10.1364/AO.33.008069|pmid=20963027|bibcode=1994ApOpt..33.8069M }}\n* {{cite book|title=Colour Physics for Industry |editor-first=Roderick |editor-last=McDonald |isbn=0-901956-70-8|publisher=[[Society of Dyers and Colourists]] |year=1997 |edition=second}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.brucelindbloom.com/ColorDifferenceCalc.html Bruce Lindbloom's color difference calculator]. Uses all metrics defined herein.\n* [http://www.ece.rochester.edu/~gsharma/ciede2000/ The CIEDE2000 Color-Difference Formula], by Gaurav Sharma. Implementations in MATLAB and Excel.\n\n{{Color topics}}\n\n[[Category:Color space]]\n[[Category:Visual perception]]\n[[Category:Color vision]]\n[[Category:Similarity and distance measures]]\n", "text_old": "The '''difference''' or '''distance''' between two colors is a [[metric (mathematics)|metric]] of interest in [[color science]]. It allows quantified examination of a notion that formerly could only be described with adjectives. Quantification of these properties is of great importance to those whose work is color-critical. Common definitions make use of the [[Euclidean distance]] in a [[device independent]] [[color space]].\n\n==Euclidean==\nAs most definitions of color difference are distances within a [[color space]], the standard means of determining distances is the Euclidean distance. If one presently has an RGB (Red, Green, Blue) tuple and wishes to find the color difference, computationally one of the easiest is to call R, G, B linear dimensions defining the color space.\n\n:<math>\\mathrm{distance} = \\sqrt{ (R_2-R_1)^2+(G_2-G_1)^2 + (B_2-B_1)^2 }</math>\n\nWhen the result should be computationally simple as well, it is often acceptable to remove the square root and simply use:\n\n:<math>\\mathrm{distance}^2 = { (R_2-R_1)^2+(G_2-G_1)^2 + (B_2-B_1)^2 }</math>\n\nThis will work in cases when a single color is to be compared to a single color and the need is to simply know whether a distance is greater. If these squared color distances are summed, such a metric effectively becomes the [[variance]] of the color distances.\n\nThere have been many attempts to weight RGB values to better fit human perception, where the components are commonly weighted (red 30%, green 59%, and blue 11%), however these are demonstrably worse at color determinations and are properly the contributions to the brightness of these colors, rather than to the degree to which human vision has less tolerance for these colors. The closer approximations would be more properly:<ref name=euc/>\n:<math>\\begin{cases}\\sqrt{ 2 \\times \\Delta R^2 + 4 \\times \\Delta G^2 + 3 \\times \\Delta B^2 } & \\bar R < 128, \\\\\n\\sqrt{ 3 \\times \\Delta R^2 + 4 \\times \\Delta G^2 + 2 \\times \\Delta B^2 } & otherwise\\end{cases}</math>, \n\nOne of the better low-cost approximations (using a color range of 0&ndash;255) combines the two cases smoothly:<ref name=euc>{{Cite web | url=http://www.compuphase.com/cmetric.htm |title = Colour metric}}</ref>\n\n:<math>\\bar r = {{C_{1,R}  + C_{2,R} } \\over 2}</math>\n:<math>\\Delta C = \\sqrt {\\left( {2 + {{\\bar r} \\over {256}}} \\right) \\times \\Delta R^2  + 4 \\times \\Delta G^2  + \\left( {2 + {{255 - \\bar r} \\over {256}}} \\right) \\times \\Delta B^2 }</math>\n\nThere are a number of color distance formulae that attempt to use color spaces like HSV with the hue as a circle, placing the various colors within a three dimensional space of either a cylinder or cone, but most of these are just modifications of RGB; without accounting for differences in human color perception they will tend to be on par with a simple Euclidean metric.\n\n==CIELAB \u0394E*==\nThe [[International Commission on Illumination]] (CIE) calls their distance metric {{math|\u0394''E''<sup>*</sup><sub>''ab''</sub>}} (also called {{math|\u0394''E*''}}, or, inaccurately, {{math|''dE''*}}, {{mvar|dE}}, or \"Delta E\") where [[delta (letter)|delta]] is a [[Greek letter]] often used to denote difference, and '''E''' stands for ''Empfindung''; German for \"sensation\". Use of this term can be traced back to [[Hermann von Helmholtz]] and [[Ewald Hering]].<ref name=\"google\">{{cite book|title=Color Vision: Perspectives from Different Disciplines|last1=Backhaus |first1=W. |last2=Kliegl |first2=R. |last3=Werner |first3=J. S. |date=1998 |publisher=Walter de Gruyter |isbn=9783110154313 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DrduOSrOFegC&pg=PA188&lpg=PA188 |page=188 |accessdate=2014-12-02}}</ref><ref name=\"google2\">{{cite book |title=Light Vision Color |last=Valberg |first=A. |date=2005|publisher=Wiley |isbn=9780470849026 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OoESifAi9ZsC |page=278 |accessdate=2014-12-02}}</ref>\n\nPerceptual non-uniformities in the underlying [[CIELAB]] color space have led to the CIE refining their definition over the years, leading to the superior (as recommended by the CIE) 1994 and 2000 formulas.<ref>Real World Color Management, Second Edition (Bruce Fraser)</ref> These non-uniformities are important because [[Color vision#Physiology of color perception|the human eye is more sensitive to certain colors than others]]. A good metric should take this into account in order for the notion of a \"[[just noticeable difference]]\" to have meaning. Otherwise, a certain {{math|\u0394''E''}} may be insignificant between two colors in one part of the color space while being significant in some other part.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20080705054344/http://www.aim-dtp.net/aim/evaluation/cie_de/index.htm Evaluation of the CIE Color Difference Formulas]</ref>\n\n===CIE76===\nThe 1976 formula is the first formula that related a measured color difference to a known set of CIELAB coordinates. This formula has been succeeded by the 1994 and 2000 formulas because the CIELAB space turned out to be not as perceptually uniform as intended, especially in the saturated regions. This means that this formula rates these colors too highly as opposed to other colors.\n\nGiven two colors in [[CIELAB color space]], <math>({L^*_1},{a^*_1},{b^*_1})</math> and <math>({L^*_2},{a^*_2},{b^*_2})</math>, the CIE76 color difference formula is defined as:\n\n:<math>\\Delta E_{ab}^* = \\sqrt{ (L^*_2-L^*_1)^2+(a^*_2-a^*_1)^2 + (b^*_2-b^*_1)^2 }</math>.\n\n<math>\\Delta E_{ab}^* \\approx 2.3</math> corresponds to a [[JND]] (just noticeable difference).<ref>{{cite book|publisher=[[CRC Press]] |title=Digital Color Imaging Handbook |year=2003 |first=Gaurav |last=Sharma |isbn=0-8493-0900-X|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OxlBqY67rl0C&pg=PA31&vq=1.42&dq=jnd+gaurav+sharma|edition=1.7.2}}</ref>\n\n===CIE94===\nThe 1976 definition was extended to address perceptual non-uniformities, while retaining the CIELAB color space, by the introduction of application-specific weights derived from an automotive paint test's tolerance data.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.colorwiki.com/wiki/Delta_E:_The_Color_Difference |title=Delta E: The Color Difference |publisher=Colorwiki.com |accessdate=2009-04-16}}</ref>\n\n\u0394''E'' (1994) is defined in the [[colorfulness#Chroma|L*C*h* color space]] with differences in lightness, chroma and hue calculated from [[CIELAB|L*a*b* coordinates]]. Given a reference color<ref>Called such because the operator is not [[commutative]]. This makes it a [[quasimetric]].</ref> <math>(L^*_1,a^*_1,b^*_1)</math> and another color <math>(L^*_2,a^*_2,b^*_2)</math>, the difference is:<ref>{{cite web|first=Bruce Justin |last=Lindbloom |url=http://www.brucelindbloom.com/Eqn_DeltaE_CIE94.html |title=Delta E (CIE 1994) |publisher=Brucelindbloom.com |accessdate=2011-03-23}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.colorpro.com/info/software/heggie.html |title=Colour Difference Software by David Heggie |publisher=Colorpro.com |date=1995-12-19 |accessdate=2009-04-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite report |title=Colorimetry - Part 4: CIE 1976 L*a*b* Colour Space |series=Draft Standard |publisher=CIE |id=CIE DS 014-4.3/E:2007 |date=2007}}</ref>\n\n:<math>\\Delta E_{94}^* = \\sqrt{ \\left(\\frac{\\Delta L^*}{k_L S_L}\\right)^2 + \\left(\\frac{\\Delta C^*_{ab}}{k_C S_C}\\right)^2 + \\left(\\frac{\\Delta H^*_{ab}}{k_H S_H}\\right)^2 }</math>\n\nwhere:\n\n:<math>\\Delta L^* = L^*_1 - L^*_2</math>\n:<math>C^*_1 = \\sqrt{ {a^*_1}^2 + {b^*_1}^2 }</math>\n:<math>C^*_2 = \\sqrt{ {a^*_2}^2 + {b^*_2}^2 }</math>\n:<math>\\Delta C^*_{ab} = C^*_1 - C^*_2</math>\n:<math>\\Delta H^*_{ab} = \\sqrt{ {\\Delta E^*_{ab}}^2 - {\\Delta L^*}^2 - {\\Delta C^*_{ab}}^2 } = \\sqrt{ {\\Delta a^*}^2 + {\\Delta b^*}^2 - {\\Delta C^*_{ab}}^2 }</math>\n:<math>\\Delta a^* = a^*_1 - a^*_2</math>\n:<math>\\Delta b^* = b^*_1 - b^*_2</math>\n:<math>S_L = 1</math>\n:<math>S_C = 1+K_1 C^*_1</math>\n:<math>S_H = 1+K_2 C^*_1</math>\n\nand where ''k<sub>C</sub>'' and ''k<sub>H</sub>'' are usually both unity and the weighting factors ''k<sub>L</sub>'', ''K''<sub>1</sub> and ''K''<sub>2</sub> depend on the application:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" border=\"1\"\n|-\n!\n! graphic arts\n! textiles\n|-\n| <math>k_L</math>\n| 1\n| 2\n|-\n| <math>K_1</math>\n| 0.045\n| 0.048\n|-\n| <math>K_2</math>\n| 0.015\n| 0.014\n|}\n\nGeometrically, the quantity <math>\\Delta H^*_{ab}</math> corresponds to the arithmetic mean of the chord lengths of the equal chroma circles of the two colors.\n<ref>{{cite book |first=Georg A. |last=Klein |title=Industrial Color Physics |page=147 |isbn=978-1-4419-1196-4|date=2010-05-18 }}</ref>\n\n===CIEDE2000===\nSince the 1994 definition did not adequately resolve the [[perceptual uniformity]] issue, the CIE refined their definition, adding five corrections:<ref>{{cite journal|title=The CIEDE2000 color-difference formula: Implementation notes, supplementary test data, and mathematical observations |journal=Color Research & Applications |publisher=[[Wiley Interscience]] |first=Gaurav |last=Sharma |first2=Wencheng |last2=Wu |first3=Edul N. |last3=Dalal |volume=30 |issue=1 |pages=21\u201330 |doi=10.1002/col.20070 |url=http://www.ece.rochester.edu/~gsharma/ciede2000/ciede2000noteCRNA.pdf |year=2005 |ref=CITEREFSharma2005 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Bruce Justin |last=Lindbloom |url=http://www.brucelindbloom.com/Eqn_DeltaE_CIE2000.html |title=Delta E (CIE 2000) |publisher=Brucelindbloom.com |accessdate=2009-04-16}}</ref>\n* A hue rotation term (R<sub>T</sub>), to deal with the problematic blue region (hue angles in the neighborhood of 275\u00b0):<ref>[http://www.brucelindbloom.com/MunsellCalcHelp.html#BluePurple The \"Blue Turns Purple\" Problem], Bruce Lindbloom</ref>\n* Compensation for neutral colors (the primed values in the L*C*h differences)\n* Compensation for lightness (S<sub>L</sub>)\n* Compensation for chroma (S<sub>C</sub>)\n* Compensation for hue (S<sub>H</sub>)\n\n:<math>\\Delta E_{00}^* = \\sqrt{ \\left(\\frac{\\Delta L'}{k_L S_L}\\right)^2 + \\left(\\frac{\\Delta C'}{k_C S_C}\\right)^2 + \\left(\\frac{\\Delta H'}{k_H S_H}\\right)^2 + R_T \\frac{\\Delta C'}{k_C S_C}\\frac{\\Delta H'}{k_H S_H} }</math>\n\n::<small>'''Note:''' The formulae below should use degrees rather than radians; the issue is significant for ''R<sub>T</sub>''.</small>\n::<small>The ''k<sub>L</sub>'', ''k<sub>C</sub>'', and ''k<sub>H</sub>'' are usually unity.</small>\n\n:<math>\\Delta L^\\prime = L^*_2 - L^*_1</math>\n\n:<math>\\bar{L}^\\prime = \\frac{L^*_1 + L^*_2}{2} \\quad \\bar{C} = \\frac{C^*_1 + C^*_2}{2}</math>\n\n:<math>\n  a_1^\\prime = a_1^* + \\frac{a_1^*}{2} \\left( 1 - \\sqrt{\\frac{\\bar{C}^7}{\\bar{C}^7 + 25^7}} \\right) \\quad\n  a_2^\\prime = a_2^* + \\frac{a_2^*}{2} \\left( 1 - \\sqrt{\\frac{\\bar{C}^7}{\\bar{C}^7 + 25^7}} \\right)\n</math>\n\n:<math>\n  \\bar{C}^\\prime = \\frac{C_1^\\prime + C_2^\\prime}{2} \\mbox{ and }\n  \\Delta{C'}=C'_2-C'_1 \\quad\n  \\mbox{where }\n    C_1^\\prime = \\sqrt{a_1^{'^2} + b_1^{*^2}} \\quad\n    C_2^\\prime = \\sqrt{a_2^{'^2} + b_2^{*^2}} \\quad\n</math>\n\n:<math>\n  h_1^\\prime=\\text{atan2} (b_1^*, a_1^\\prime) \\mod 360^\\circ, \\quad\n  h_2^\\prime=\\text{atan2} (b_2^*, a_2^\\prime) \\mod 360^\\circ\n</math>\n:: <small>'''Note:''' The inverse tangent (tan<sup>&minus;1</sup>) can be computed using a common library routine <code>atan2(b, a&prime;)</code> which usually has a range from &minus;&pi; to &pi; radians; color specifications are given in 0 to 360 degrees, so some adjustment is needed. The inverse tangent is indeterminate if both ''a&prime;'' and ''b'' are zero (which also means that the corresponding ''C&prime;'' is zero); in that case, set the hue angle to zero. See {{harvnb|Sharma|2005|loc=eqn. 7}}.</small>\n\n:<math>\n  \\Delta h' = \\begin{cases}\n    h_2^\\prime - h_1^\\prime & \\left| h_1^\\prime - h_2^\\prime \\right| \\leq 180^\\circ \\\\\n    h_2^\\prime - h_1^\\prime + 360^\\circ & \\left| h_1^\\prime - h_2^\\prime \\right| > 180^\\circ, h_2^\\prime \\leq h_1^\\prime \\\\\n    h_2^\\prime - h_1^\\prime - 360^\\circ & \\left| h_1^\\prime - h_2^\\prime \\right| > 180^\\circ, h_2^\\prime > h_1^\\prime\n  \\end{cases}\n</math>\n:: <small>'''Note:''' When either ''C&prime;''<sub>1</sub> or ''C&prime;''<sub>2</sub> is zero, then &Delta;h&prime; is irrelevant and may be set to zero. See {{harvnb|Sharma|2005|loc=eqn. 10}}.</small>\n\n:<math>\n  \\Delta H^\\prime = 2 \\sqrt{C_1^\\prime C_2^\\prime} \\sin (\\Delta h^\\prime/2), \\quad \\bar{H}^\\prime=\\begin{cases}\n    (h_1^\\prime + h_2^\\prime)/2 & \\left| h_1^\\prime - h_2^\\prime \\right| \\leq 180^\\circ \\\\\n    (h_1^\\prime + h_2^\\prime + 360^\\circ)/2 & \\left| h_1^\\prime - h_2^\\prime \\right| > 180^\\circ, h_1^\\prime + h_2^\\prime < 360^\\circ \\\\\n    (h_1^\\prime + h_2^\\prime - 360^\\circ)/2 & \\left| h_1^\\prime - h_2^\\prime \\right| > 180^\\circ, h_1^\\prime + h_2^\\prime \\geq 360^\\circ \n    \\end{cases}\n</math>\n:: <small>'''Note:''' When either ''C&prime;''<sub>1</sub> or ''C&prime;''<sub>2</sub> is zero, then {{overbar|H}}&prime; is ''h&prime;''<sub>1</sub>+''h&prime;''<sub>2</sub> (no divide by 2; essentially, if one angle is indeterminate, then use the other angle as the average; relies on indeterminate angle being set to zero). See {{harvnb|Sharma|2005|loc=eqn. 7 and p. 23}} stating most implementations on the internet at the time had \"an error in the computation of average hue\".</small>\n\n:<math>\n  T = 1 - 0.17 \\cos ( \\bar{H}^\\prime - 30^\\circ )\n        + 0.24 \\cos (2\\bar{H}^\\prime)\n        + 0.32 \\cos (3\\bar{H}^\\prime + 6^\\circ )\n        - 0.20 \\cos (4\\bar{H}^\\prime - 63^\\circ)\n</math>\n\n:<math>\n  S_L = 1 + \\frac{0.015 \\left( \\bar{L}^\\prime - 50 \\right)^2}{\\sqrt{20 + {\\left(\\bar{L}^\\prime - 50 \\right)}^2} } \\quad\n  S_C = 1+0.045 \\bar{C}^\\prime \\quad\n  S_H = 1+0.015 \\bar{C}^\\prime T\n</math>\n\n:<math>R_T = -2 \\sqrt{\\frac{\\bar{C}'^7}{\\bar{C}'^7+25^7}} \\sin \\left[ 60^\\circ \\cdot \\exp \\left( -\\left[ \\frac{\\bar{H}'-275^\\circ}{25^\\circ} \\right]^2 \\right) \\right]</math>\n\n===CMC l:c (1984)===\nIn 1984, the Colour Measurement Committee of the [[Society of Dyers and Colourists]] defined a difference measure, also based on the L*C*h color model. Named after the developing committee, their metric is called '''CMC l:c'''. The [[quasimetric]] has two parameters: lightness (l) and chroma (c), allowing the users to weight the difference based on the ratio of l:c that is deemed appropriate for the application. Commonly used values are 2:1<ref>Meaning that the lightness contributes ''half'' as much to the difference (or, identically, is allowed ''twice'' the tolerance) as the chroma</ref> for acceptability and 1:1 for the threshold of imperceptibility.\n\nThe distance of a color <math>(L^*_2,C^*_2,h_2)</math> to a reference <math>(L^*_1,C^*_1,h_1)</math> is:<ref>{{cite web|first=Bruce Justin |last=Lindbloom |url=http://www.brucelindbloom.com/Eqn_DeltaE_CMC.html |title=Delta E (CMC) |publisher=Brucelindbloom.com |accessdate=2009-04-16}}</ref>\n\n: <math>\\Delta E^*_{CMC} = \\sqrt{ \\left( \\frac{L^*_2-L^*_1}{l S_L} \\right)^2 + \\left( \\frac{C^*_2-C^*_1}{c S_C} \\right)^2 + \\left( \\frac{\\Delta H^*_{ab}}{S_H} \\right)^2 }</math>\n\n: <math>S_L=\\begin{cases} 0.511 & L^*_1 < 16 \\\\ \\frac{0.040975 L^*_1}{1+0.01765 L^*_1} & L^*_1 \\geq 16 \\end{cases} \\quad S_C=\\frac{0.0638 C^*_1}{1+0.0131 C^*_1} + 0.638 \\quad S_H=S_C (FT+1-F)</math>\n\n: <math>F = \\sqrt{\\frac{C^{*^4}_1}{C^{*^4}_1+1900}} \\quad T=\\begin{cases} 0.56 + |0.2 \\cos (h_1+168^\\circ)| & 164^\\circ \\leq h_1 \\leq 345^\\circ \\\\ 0.36 + |0.4 \\cos (h_1+35^\\circ) | & \\mbox{otherwise} \\end{cases}</math>\n\nCMC l:c is designed to be used with [[CIE Standard Illuminant D65|D65]] and the [[CIE 1931 color space#CIE standard observer|CIE Supplementary Observer]].<ref>{{cite journal| url=http://www.hunterlab.com/appnotes/an10_96ar.pdf| title=CMC| journal=Insight on Color| volume=8| issue=13| date=1-15 October 1996| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060312161957/http://www.hunterlab.com/appnotes/an10_96ar.pdf| archive-date=2006-03-12}}</ref> The formula is not a metric but rather a quasimetric because it violates symmetry, parameter T is based on the hue of the <math>h_1</math> alone. This reference color means that the color difference from the first color to the second color is different than the color distance from the second color is to the first.\n\n===Tolerance===\n[[Image:CIExy1931 MacAdam.png|250px|right|thumb|A MacAdam diagram in the [[CIE 1931 color space]]. The ellipses are shown ten times their actual size.]]\n\n'''Tolerancing''' concerns the question \"What is a set of colors that are imperceptibly/acceptably close to a given reference?\" If the distance measure is '''''perceptually uniform''''', then the answer is simply \"the set of points whose distance to the reference is less than the just-noticeable-difference (JND) threshold.\" This requires a perceptually uniform metric in order for the threshold to be constant throughout the [[gamut]] (range of colors). Otherwise, the threshold will be a function of the reference color\u2014cumbersome as a practical guide.\n\nIn the [[CIE 1931 color space]], for example, the tolerance contours are defined by the [[MacAdam ellipse]], which holds L* (lightness) fixed. As can be observed on the adjacent diagram, the [[ellipse]]s denoting the tolerance contours vary in size. It is partly this non-uniformity that led to the creation of [[CIELUV]] and [[CIELAB]].\n\nMore generally, if the lightness is allowed to vary, then we find the tolerance set to be [[ellipsoid]]al. Increasing the weighting factor in the aforementioned distance expressions has the effect of increasing the size of the ellipsoid along the respective axis.<ref name=\"xrite\">{{cite web|url=http://www.xrite.com/documents/literature/en/L10-024_Color_Tolerance_en.pdf|date=14 January 1998|author=Susan Hughes|title=A guide to Understanding Color Tolerancing|accessdate=2014-12-02|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151010064956/http://www.xrite.com/documents/literature/en/L10-024_Color_Tolerance_en.pdf|archivedate=10 October 2015}}</ref>\n\n<!-- A diagram would handily illustrate the last paragraph. I am not going to post a {{reqdiagram}} tag here in order not to make the article ugly, but you can contribute if you like. -->\n\n{{clear}}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[CIELAB]]\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite journal|title=Historical development of CIE recommended color difference equations|first=Alan R.|last=Robertson|journal=Color Research & Application|year=1990|volume=15|issue=3|pages=167\u2013170|doi=10.1002/col.5080150308|url=http://www3.interscience.wiley.com/cgi-bin/fulltext/114184816/PDFSTART}}{{dead link|date=February 2019|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}\n* {{cite journal|title=Uniformity of some recent color metrics tested with an accurate color-difference tolerance dataset |first=M. |last=Melgosa |last2=Quesada |first2=J. J. |last3=Hita |first3=E.|date=December 1994|journal=[[Applied Optics]]|volume=33|issue=34|pages=8069\u20138077|doi=10.1364/AO.33.008069|pmid=20963027|bibcode=1994ApOpt..33.8069M }}\n* {{cite book|title=Colour Physics for Industry |editor-first=Roderick |editor-last=McDonald |isbn=0-901956-70-8|publisher=[[Society of Dyers and Colourists]] |year=1997 |edition=second}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.brucelindbloom.com/ColorDifferenceCalc.html Bruce Lindbloom's color difference calculator]. Uses all metrics defined herein.\n* [http://www.ece.rochester.edu/~gsharma/ciede2000/ The CIEDE2000 Color-Difference Formula], by Gaurav Sharma. Implementations in MATLAB and Excel.\n\n{{Color topics}}\n\n[[Category:Color space]]\n[[Category:Visual perception]]\n[[Category:Color vision]]\n[[Category:Similarity and distance measures]]\n", "name_user": "Comp.arch", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Color_difference"}
{"title_page": "Battle of Sarantaporo", "text_new": "{{good article}}\n{{Infobox Military Conflict\n|conflict=Battle of Sarantaporo\n|partof=the [[First Balkan War]]   \n|image=Sarantaporo.png\n|image_size=250px\n|caption=Map of the battle\n|date=9\u201310 October 1912 ([[Old Style and New Style dates|O.S.]])    \n|place=[[Sarantaporo]], [[Manastir Vilayet]], [[Ottoman Empire]] (present-day [[Greece]])  \n|result= Greek victory \n* Greek army captures [[Servia, Greece|Servia]] and [[Kozani]]\n|map_type    = Greece\n| map_label   =Sarantaporo\n|map_relief  = yes\n|alt         = A relief map of modern day Greece, with the location of the battle marked.\n|map_caption ={{center|Location of the battle in present day Greece}}\n|coordinates={{coord|40.0400|N|22.0300|E|display=title}}\n|combatant1={{flagicon|Greece|royal}} [[Kingdom of Greece|Greece]]  \n|combatant2={{flag|Ottoman Empire}}   \n|commander1=Crown Prince [[Constantine I of Greece|Constantine]]\n|commander2=General [[Hasan Tahsin Pasha]]\n|units1=[[Order of battle of the Hellenic Army in the First Balkan War#Army of Thessaly|Army of Thessaly]]\n*[[1st Infantry Division (Greece)|1st Infantry Division]]\n*[[2nd Infantry Division (Greece)|2nd Infantry Division]]\n*[[3rd Infantry Division (Greece)|3rd Infantry Division]]\n*[[4th Infantry Division (Greece)|4th Infantry Division]]   \n*[[5th Infantry Division (Greece)|5th Infantry Division]]\n|units2=[[VIII Corps (Ottoman Empire)|VIII Corps]]\n*[[22nd Infantry Division (Ottoman Empire)|22nd Infantry Division]]\n*Nasli\u00e7 Division\n|strength1=''5 divisions''\n|strength2=''2 divisions''\n|casualties1=182 killed<br>1,000 wounded \n|casualties2=500 killed<br />1,000 wounded<br />22\u201325 field artillery pieces\n}}   \n{{Campaignbox First Balkan War}}\n\nThe '''Battle of Sarantaporo''', also variously transliterated as '''Sarantaporon''' or '''Sarandaporon''' ({{lang-el|\u039c\u03ac\u03c7\u03b7 \u03c4\u03bf\u03c5 \u03a3\u03b1\u03c1\u03b1\u03bd\u03c4\u03b1\u03c0\u03cc\u03c1\u03bf\u03c5}}, {{lang-tr|Sarantaporo Muharebesi}}), took place on 9\u201310 October ([[Old Style and New Style dates|O.S.]]), 1912.{{refn|9\u201310 October 1912 Old Style corresponds to 22\u201323 October 1912 New Style.{{sfn|Blackburn|Holford-Strevens|1999|p=788}}|group=Note}} It was the first major battle fought between [[Kingdom of Greece|Greek]] forces under Crown Prince [[Constantine I of Greece|Constantine]] and [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman]] forces under General [[Hasan Tahsin Pasha]] during the [[First Balkan War]]. The battle began when the Greek army attacked the Ottoman defensive line at the Sarantaporo pass, which connected [[Thessaly]] with central [[Macedonia (region)|Macedonia]].\n\nDespite being perceived as impregnable by its defenders, the main body of the Greek forces managed to advance deep inside the pass, while auxiliary units broke through the Ottoman flanks. The Ottomans abandoned their defensive line during the night, fearing encirclement. The Greek victory at Sarantaporo opened the way for the capture of [[Servia, Greece|Servia]] and [[Kozani]].\n\n==Background==\nFollowing the conclusion of the [[Greek War of Independence]], the [[Megali Idea]] (Great Idea) ideology came to dominate Greek foreign policy. The ultimate goal of the Megali Idea was the incorporation of all areas traditionally populated by Greeks into an independent Greek state.{{sfn|Klapsis|2009|pp=127\u2013131}} The disastrous Greek defeat in the short [[Greco-Turkish War (1897)|Greco-Turkish War]] of 1897 exposed major flaws in the [[Greek Army]]'s organization, training and logistics. Upon his appointment in December 1905, [[Georgios Theotokis]] became the first postwar Greek prime minister to focus his attention on strengthening the army. He established the National Defense Fund which financed the purchase of large quantities of ammunition. In addition a new [[table of organization]] was introduced for the country's [[Greek Navy|navy]] and army, the latter being augmented by numerous artillery batteries. Theotokis' resignation in January 1909 and the perceived neglect of the armed forces by his successor resulted in the [[Goudi coup]] seven months later. Rather than taking power for themselves, the putschists invited [[Crete|Cretan]] politician [[Eleftherios Venizelos]] to rule the country.{{sfn|Kargakos|2012|pp=19\u201321}} Venizelos followed in Theotokis' footsteps by rearming and retraining the military, enacting extensive fortification and infrastructure works, purchasing new weapons, and recalling the [[Military reserve force|reservists]] for training.{{sfn|Katsikostas|2014|pp=5\u20136}}\n\nThe climax of this effort was the invitation in 1911 of a [[British naval mission to Greece (1911\u20131915)|British naval mission]] and a [[French military mission to Greece (1911\u20131914)|French military mission]].{{sfn|Katsikostas|2014|pp=5\u20136}} The British mission was headed by Rear Admiral [[Lionel Grant Tufnell]], who placed an emphasis on gunnery practice and fleet maneuvers, while his assistants introduced a new fuse for the [[Whitehead torpedo]].{{sfn|Hooton|2014|p=65}} The French mission under Brigadier General [[Joseph Paul Eydoux]] focused its attention on improving discipline and training senior officers in large [[Formation (military)|formation]] operations.{{sfn|Katsikostas|2014|p=12}} The [[Hellenic Military Academy]] was modeled after the [[\u00c9cole sp\u00e9ciale militaire de Saint-Cyr]] shifting its focus from artillery and engineer training towards that of infantry and cavalry.{{sfn|Veremis|1976|p=115}}\n\nAfter being informed of a [[Kingdom of Serbia|Serbo]]-[[Kingdom of Bulgaria|Bulgarian]] alliance, Venizelos ordered his ambassador in [[Sofia]] to prepare a Greco-Bulgarian defense agreement by 14 April 1912. This was due to fears that should Greece fail to participate in a future war against the [[Ottoman Empire|Ottomans]] it would be unable to capture the Greek majority areas of [[Macedonia (region)|Macedonia]]. The treaty was signed on 15 July 1912, with the two countries agreeing to assist each other in case of a defensive war and to safeguard the rights of Christian populations in Ottoman-held Macedonia, thus joining the loose [[Balkan League]] alliance with Serbia, [[Kingdom of Montenegro|Montenegro]] and Bulgaria. Fearing a new war in the Balkans, the Ottomans mobilized their armed forces on 14 September and began transferring units to [[Thrace]]; the Balkan League responded in kind.{{sfn|Kargakos|2012|pp=26\u201329}} On 30 September, the League presented the Ottomans with a list of demands regarding the rights of its Christian population. The Ottoman Empire rebuffed the demands, recalled its ambassadors in Sofia, Belgrade and Athens and expelled the League's negotiators on 4 October. The League declared [[First Balkan War|war]] against the Ottomans, while Montenegro had already began military operations on 25 September.{{sfn|Kargakos|2012|pp=35\u201338}}\n\n==Prelude==\nGreece dispatched the [[Army of Epirus]] and the [[Army of Thessaly]] to its frontiers in [[Epirus]] and [[Thessaly]] respectively. The latter numbered 100,000 men, and was divided into seven divisions: namely the [[1st Infantry Division (Greece)|1st]], the [[2nd Infantry Division (Greece)|2nd]], the [[3rd Infantry Division (Greece)|3rd]], the [[4th Infantry Division (Greece)|4th]], the [[5th Infantry Division (Greece)|5th]], the [[6th Infantry Division (Greece)|6th]] and the [[7th Mechanized Infantry Brigade (Greece)|7th Infantry Divisions]], as well as a cavalry brigade and four independent [[Evzones]] battalions. The Army of Thessaly was commanded by Crown Prince [[Constantine I of Greece|Constantine]].{{sfn|Christopoulos|Bastias|1977|pp=289\u2013290}} Facing the Greeks in Thessaly was the Ottoman [[VIII Corps (Ottoman Empire)|VIII Corps]] under General [[Hasan Tahsin Pasha]] which included three divisions: the regular (''nizamiye'') [[22nd Infantry Division (Ottoman Empire)|22nd Division]] and the reserve (''redif'') Nasli\u00e7 and Ayd\u0131n Divisions{{sfn|Erickson|2003|p=170}} which, combined with the Ottoman garrisons in western Macedonia, totaled 35,000\u201340,000 men.{{sfn|Christopoulos|Bastias|1977|p=290}}\n\nThe Army of Thessaly crossed into Ottoman territory in the early morning hours of 5 October, finding most border posts to be abandoned, with the garrisons at Melouna Pass, Profitis Ilias and Tsouka resisting for several hours before retreating. The first major clashes took place the following day when the 1st and 2nd Greek Divisions attacked hastily organized defenses north of [[Elassona]]. Elassona was defended by three infantry battalions, two artillery batteries and half a squadron of cavalry.{{sfn|Christopoulos|Bastias|1977|p=290}} The battle for Elassona lasted for three hours, with the Ottomans retreating to avoid encirclement, thus giving the troops manning the main defensive line at Sarantaporo additional time to reinforce their positions.{{sfn|Kargakos|2012|pp=44\u201345}} The Greeks went on to advance {{convert|20|km|miles}} into the Elassona plateau without encountering any resistance.{{sfn|Kargakos|2012|p=47}} Between 7 and 8 October, Greek troops regrouped in front of Sarantaporo and dispatched cavalry reconnaissance patrols towards the Ottoman positions, locating the headquarters of the Ottoman VIII Corps at Hania Viglas and those of a reserve division at Glikovo.{{sfn|Christopoulos|Bastias|1977|p=290}}\n\nSituated between the Vigla and Amorves mountains, Sarantaporo was a narrow mountain pass, the only one connecting Thessaly with central Macedonia; it spanned some {{convert|7\u20138|km|miles|sigfig=1}}. Having ceded Thessaly to Greece in the [[Convention of Constantinople (1881)]], the Ottomans had been methodically reinforcing their positions around Sarantaporo in anticipation of a future war.{{sfn|Kargakos|2012|p=48}} The Ottomans had organized their defenses under the guidance of German military advisors, placing their artillery batteries and infantry in sheltered, camouflaged trenches on the ravine's steep slopes, allowing them to accurately fire along its entire length. Considered to be nearly impenetrable it was dubbed \"the graveyard of the Greek Army\" by  the Prussian Field Marshal [[Colmar Freiherr von der Goltz]].{{sfn|Dimitracopoulos|1992|p=42}}\n\n==Battle==\nAt 7 a.m. on 9 October, the Greek infantry began its assault on Sarantaporo. The 1st, 2nd and 3rd Divisions attacked the Ottoman main line frontally, their advance hampered by accurate Ottoman rifle and artillery fire and the ruggedness of the terrain. In the meantime, the 4th Division conducted a flanking maneuver from the west with the intention of occupying the [[Pyli|Porta Pass]], and striking the rear of the Ottoman positions.{{sfn|Christopoulos|Bastias|1977|p=291}} The 5th Division advanced further to the west towards the village of Zampourda which was situated on the other bank of the [[Haliacmon]] River, with the intention of protecting the left flank of the Greek forces emerging from the Sarantaporo pass. The cavalry brigade moved on the extreme west along the road towards [[Servia, Greece|Servia]], planning to block the bridge across the Haliacmon.{{sfn|Kargakos|2012|p=51}} Attacking from the east of the pass the Konstantinopoulos Evzone detachment overcame stiff resistance at Vlacholeivado and captured the village, but failing to advance further due to heavy fog.{{sfn|Christopoulos|Bastias|1977|p=291}}{{sfn|Apostolidis|1913|pp=207\u2013209}} At 2 p.m., the main bulk of the Greek artillery was brought to the main line, joining the engagement. Despite suffering heavy casualties, the three divisions had halted some {{convert|500-700|m|yards|sigfig=1}} from the Ottoman trenches intending to launch a final assault the following morning.{{sfn|Christopoulos|Bastias|1977|p=291}}\n\nThe 4th Division fought its way through the villages of Metaxas and Rachovo. Upon reaching the Porta Pass it engaged in a bloody clash with the defenders, securing its objective at 5 p.m.{{sfn|Kargakos|2012|p=53}} The 5th Division and the Gennadis Evzone detachment were confronted by four Ottoman reserve battalions at Lazarades which held their ground until sunset.{{sfn|Christopoulos|Bastias|1977|p=291}} The commander of the cavalry brigade ordered his unit to encamp at Loudani, refusing to advance further because of the resistance offered by the Ottomans at Lazarades. Fearing that they would be encircled by the Konstantinopoulos Evzone detachment, the Ottomans began to withdraw at 7 p.m., towards their second defensive line at Hani 739, under the cover of the night. Before retreating they fired a 20-minute artillery barrage on Greek positions along the entire frontline. Unaware of the Ottoman retreat the Greeks failed to use the opportunity and cut their access to the bridge across the Haliacmon. Upon reaching their second defensive line, the Ottomans became aware of the 4th Divisions' seizure of Porta Pass and panic spread in their ranks and many soldiers fled, abandoning their equipment.{{sfn|Apostolidis|1913|pp=203\u2013205}} On the morning of 10 October, the 4th Division charged down the northern slope of the Rahovo Mountain, surprising the Ottoman infantry and artillerymen who abandoned over twenty [[Krupp gun]]s and engaged in a disorganized retreat.{{sfn|Dimitracopoulos|1992|p=44}}{{sfn|Erickson|2003|pp=218\u2013219}} The Greek cavalry's indecision once again enabled the fleeing Ottomans to safely reach Servia and [[Kozani]].{{sfn|Kargakos|2012|pp=56\u201357}}\n\n==Aftermath==\nAt 4 p.m. on 10 October, the 4th Division entered Servia, witnessing 75 to 90 severed human heads belonging to local Christians lined up on either side of one of its streets.{{sfn|Dimitracopoulos|1992|p=44}}{{sfn|Christopoulos|Bastias|1977|p=292}} Following the declaration of war local authorities had detained all the Christian dignitaries from Servia and the surrounding villages with the intention of massacring them, a plan that was thwarted by Ottoman officer Omer Bey. However, upon realizing the imminent defeat of the Ottoman troops at Sarantaporo, the town's Muslim population massacred 117 local Christians.{{sfn|Kargakos|2012|pp=58\u201359}} By 11 October, the entirety of the Army of Thessaly had reached the banks of the Haliacmon, while the Greek cavalry entered Kozani unopposed,{{sfn|Christopoulos|Bastias|1977|p=292}} opening the way for the Greeks to advance towards the Greek majority city of [[Thessaloniki]] and assist the Serbs at [[Bitola|Monastir]].{{sfn|Dimitracopoulos|1992|p=46}} On 13 October, the Greek army transferred its general headquarters to Kozani; the following day King [[George I of Greece|George I]] arrived in the city, ordering the army to march towards Thessaloniki and [[Veroia]].{{sfn|Apostolidis|1913|pp=241\u2013243}} Greek casualties in the battle of Sarantaporo numbered 182 killed and over 1,000 wounded,{{sfn|Christopoulos|Bastias|1977|p=292}} while the Ottomans lost approximately 500 killed, 1,000 wounded, around 22 to 25 [[field artillery]] pieces captured and other significant material losses.{{sfn|Dimitracopoulos|1992|p=44}}{{sfn|Erickson|2003|pp=218\u2013219}}\n\nBy May 1913, the numerically inferior Ottomans had suffered a series of serious defeats to the League's armies on all fronts. The League had captured most of the Ottoman Empire's European territories and was rapidly approaching [[Constantinople]]. On 30 May, the two sides signed the [[Treaty of London (1913)|Treaty of London]] which granted the League's members all Ottoman lands west of [[Enos, Turkey|Enos]] on the [[Aegean Sea]] and north of [[K\u0131y\u0131k\u00f6y|Midia]] on the [[Black Sea]], as well as Crete. The fate of [[Independent Albania|Albania]] and the Ottoman-held Aegean islands was to be determined by the [[International relations of the Great Powers (1814\u20131919)|Great Powers]].{{sfn|Christopoulos|Bastias|1977|pp=330\u2013332}}\n\n==Notes==\n;Footnotes\n{{Reflist|group=Note}}\n\n;Citations\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==References==\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book |last=Apostolidis |first=Dimitrios |title=\u039f \u03bd\u03b9\u03ba\u03b7\u03c6\u03cc\u03c1\u03bf\u03c2 \u03b5\u03bb\u03bb\u03b7\u03bd\u03bf\u03c4\u03bf\u03c5\u03c1\u03ba\u03b9\u03ba\u03cc\u03c2 \u03c0\u03cc\u03bb\u03b5\u03bc\u03bf\u03c2 \u03c4\u03bf\u03c5 1912-1913|trans-title=The Victorious Greco-Turkish War of 1912-1913|volume=I|publisher=Estia|location=Athens|language=Greek|year=1913|url=https://anemi.lib.uoc.gr/metadata/8/d/1/metadata-9272bd94229998ed96a378ab0f986a22_1270023610.tkl|accessdate=13 November 2019|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Blackburn|first1=Bonnie|last2=Holford-Strevens|first2=Leofranc|title=The Oxford Companion to the Year|year=1999|publisher=Oxford University Press|location=Oxford|isbn=0-19-214231-3|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |first1=Georgios|last1=Christopoulos|first2=Ioannis|last2=Bastias|title=\u0399\u03c3\u03c4\u03bf\u03c1\u03af\u03b1 \u03c4\u03bf\u03c5 \u0395\u03bb\u03bb\u03b7\u03bd\u03b9\u03ba\u03bf\u03cd \u0395\u03b8\u03bd\u03bf\u03c5\u03c2: \u039d\u03b5\u03ce\u03c4\u03b5\u03c1\u03bf\u03c2 \u0395\u03bb\u03bb\u03b7\u03bd\u03b9\u03c3\u03bc\u03cc\u03c2 \u03b1\u03c0\u03bf \u03c4\u03bf 1881 \u03c9\u03c2 1913|trans-title=History of the Greek Nation: Modern Greece from 1881 until 1913 |volume=XIV |publisher=Ekdotiki Athinon|language=Greek|location=Athens|year=1977 |isbn=960-213-110-1|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Dimitracopoulos |first=Anastasios |title=The First Balkan War Through the Pages of Review L'Illustration |year=1992 |publisher=Hellenic Committee of Military History|location=Athens |oclc= 37043754| ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Erickson |first=Edward |title=Defeat in Detail: The Ottoman Army in the Balkans, 1912-1913 |year=2003|publisher=Praeger|location=Westport | isbn =978-0-275-97888-4| ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Hooton |first=Edward|title=Prelude to the First World War: The Balkan Wars 1912-1913 |year=2014|publisher=Fonthill Media|lo