n War]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1912]]\n[[Category:Battles involving the Ottoman Empire]]\n[[Category:Battles involving Greece]]\n[[Category:1912 in Greece]]\n[[Category:1912 in the Ottoman Empire]]\n[[Category:Manastir Vilayet]]\n[[Category:Modern history of Thessaly]]\n[[Category:October 1912 events]]\n", "text_old": "{{good article}}\n{{Infobox Military Conflict\n|conflict=Battle of Sarantaporo\n|partof=the [[First Balkan War]]   \n|image=Sarantaporo.png\n|image_size=250px\n|caption=Map of the battle\n|date=9\u201310 October 1912 ([[Old Style and New Style dates|O.S.]])    \n|place=[[Sarantaporo]], [[Manastir Vilayet]], [[Ottoman Empire]] (present-day [[Greece]])  \n|result= Greek victory \n* Greek army captures [[Servia, Greece|Servia]] and [[Kozani]]\n|map_type    = Greece\n| map_label   =Sarantaporo\n|map_relief  = yes\n|alt         = A relief map of modern day Greece, with the location of the battle marked.\n|map_caption ={{center|Location of the battle in present day Greece}}\n|coordinates={{coord|40.0400|N|22.0300|E|display=title}}\n|combatant1={{flagicon|Greece|royal}} [[Kingdom of Greece|Greece]]  \n|combatant2={{flag|Ottoman Empire}}   \n|commander1=Crown Prince [[Constantine I of Greece|Constantine]]\n|commander2=General [[Hasan Tahsin Pasha]]\n|units1=[[Order of battle of the Hellenic Army in the First Balkan War#Army of Thessaly|Army of Thessaly]]\n*[[1st Infantry Division (Greece)|1st Infantry Division]]\n*[[2nd Infantry Division (Greece)|2nd Infantry Division]]\n*[[3rd Infantry Division (Greece)|3rd Infantry Division]]\n*[[4th Infantry Division (Greece)|4th Infantry Division]]   \n*[[5th Infantry Division (Greece)|5th Infantry Division]]\n|units2=[[VIII Corps (Ottoman Empire)|VIII Corps]]\n*[[22nd Infantry Division (Ottoman Empire)|22nd Infantry Division]]\n*Nasli\u00e7 Division\n|strength1=''5 divisions''\n|strength2=''2 divisions''\n|casualties1=182 killed<br>1,000 wounded \n|casualties2=500 killed<br />1,000 wounded<br />22\u201325 field artillery pieces\n}}   \n{{Campaignbox First Balkan War}}\n\nThe '''Battle of Sarantaporo''', also variously transliterated as '''Sarantaporon''' or '''Sarandaporon''' ({{lang-el|\u039c\u03ac\u03c7\u03b7 \u03c4\u03bf\u03c5 \u03a3\u03b1\u03c1\u03b1\u03bd\u03c4\u03b1\u03c0\u03cc\u03c1\u03bf\u03c5}}, {{lang-tr|Sarantaporo Muharebesi}}), took place on 9\u201310 October ([[Old Style and New Style dates|O.S.]]), 1912.{{refn|9\u201310 October 1912 Old Style corresponds to 22\u201323 October 1912 New Style.{{sfn|Blackburn|Holford-Strevens|1999|p=788}}|group=Note}} It was the first major battle fought between [[Kingdom of Greece|Greek]] forces under Crown Prince [[Constantine I of Greece|Constantine]] and [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman]] forces under General [[Hasan Tahsin Pasha]] during the [[First Balkan War]]. The battle began when the Greek army attacked the Ottoman defensive line at the Sarantaporo pass, which connected [[Thessaly]] with central [[Macedonia (region)|Macedonia]].\n\nDespite being perceived as impregnable by its defenders, the main body of the Greek forces managed to advance deep inside the pass, while auxiliary units broke through the Ottoman flanks. The Ottomans abandoned their defensive line during the night, fearing encirclement. The Greek victory at Sarantaporo opened the way for the capture of [[Servia, Greece|Servia]] and [[Kozani]].\n\n==Background==\nFollowing the conclusion of the [[Greek War of Independence]], the [[Megali Idea]] (Great Idea) ideology came to dominate Greek foreign policy. The ultimate goal of the Megali Idea was the incorporation of all areas traditionally populated by Greeks into an independent Greek state.{{sfn|Klapsis|2009|pp=127\u2013131}} The disastrous Greek defeat in the short [[Greco-Turkish War (1897)|Greco-Turkish War]] of 1897 exposed major flaws in the [[Greek Army]]'s organization, training and logistics. Upon his appointment in December 1905, [[Georgios Theotokis]] became the first postwar Greek prime minister to focus his attention on strengthening the army. He established the National Defense Fund which financed the purchase of large quantities of ammunition. In addition a new [[table of organization]] was introduced for the country's [[Greek Navy|navy]] and army, the latter being augmented by numerous artillery batteries. Theotokis' resignation in January 1909 and the perceived neglect of the armed forces by his successor resulted in the [[Goudi coup]] seven months later. Rather than taking power for themselves, the putschists invited [[Crete|Cretan]] politician [[Eleftherios Venizelos]] to rule the country.{{sfn|Kargakos|2012|pp=19\u201321}} Venizelos followed in Theotokis' footsteps by rearming and retraining the military, enacting extensive fortification and infrastructure works, purchasing new weapons, and recalling the [[Military reserve force|reservists]] for training.{{sfn|Katsikostas|2014|pp=5\u20136}}\n\nThe climax of this effort was the invitation in 1911 of a [[British naval mission to Greece (1911\u20131915)|British naval mission]] and a [[French military mission to Greece (1911\u20131914)|French military mission]].{{sfn|Katsikostas|2014|pp=5\u20136}} The British mission was headed by Rear Admiral [[Lionel Grant Tufnell]], who placed an emphasis on gunnery practice and fleet maneuvers, while his assistants introduced a new fuse for the [[Whitehead torpedo]].{{sfn|Hooton|2014|p=65}} The French mission under Brigadier General [[Joseph Paul Eydoux]] focused its attention on improving discipline and training senior officers in large [[Formation (military)|formation]] operations.{{sfn|Katsikostas|2014|p=12}} The [[Hellenic Military Academy]] was modeled after the [[\u00c9cole sp\u00e9ciale militaire de Saint-Cyr]] shifting its focus from artillery and engineer training towards that of infantry and cavalry.{{sfn|Veremis|1976|p=115}}\n\nAfter being informed of a [[Kingdom of Serbia|Serbo]]-[[Kingdom of Bulgaria|Bulgarian]] alliance, Venizelos ordered his ambassador in [[Sofia]] to prepare a Greco-Bulgarian defense agreement by 14 April 1912. This was due to fears that should Greece fail to participate in a future war against the [[Ottoman Empire|Ottomans]] it would be unable to capture the Greek majority areas of [[Macedonia (region)|Macedonia]]. The treaty was signed on 15 July 1912, with the two countries agreeing to assist each other in case of a defensive war and to safeguard the rights of Christian populations in Ottoman-held Macedonia, thus joining the loose [[Balkan League]] alliance with Serbia, [[Kingdom of Montenegro|Montenegro]] and Bulgaria. Fearing a new war in the Balkans, the Ottomans mobilized their armed forces on 14 September and began transferring units to [[Thrace]]; the Balkan League responded in kind.{{sfn|Kargakos|2012|pp=26\u201329}} On 30 September, the League presented the Ottomans with a list of demands regarding the rights of its Christian population. The Ottoman Empire rebuffed the demands, recalled its ambassadors in Sofia, Belgrade and Athens and expelled the League's negotiators on 4 October. The League declared [[First Balkan War|war]] against the Ottomans, while Montenegro had already began military operations on 25 September.{{sfn|Kargakos|2012|pp=35\u201338}}\n\n==Prelude==\nGreece dispatched the [[Army of Epirus]] and the [[Army of Thessaly]] to its frontiers in [[Epirus]] and [[Thessaly]] respectively. The latter numbered 100,000 men, and was divided into seven divisions: namely the [[1st Infantry Division (Greece)|1st]], the [[2nd Infantry Division (Greece)|2nd]], the [[3rd Infantry Division (Greece)|3rd]], the [[4th Infantry Division (Greece)|4th]], the [[5th Infantry Division (Greece)|5th]], the [[6th Infantry Division (Greece)|6th]] and the [[7th Mechanized Infantry Brigade (Greece)|7th Infantry Divisions]], as well as a cavalry brigade and four independent [[Evzones]] battalions. The Army of Thessaly was commanded by Crown Prince [[Constantine I of Greece|Constantine]].{{sfn|Christopoulos|Bastias|1977|pp=289\u2013290}} Facing the Greeks in Thessaly was the Ottoman [[VIII Corps (Ottoman Empire)|VIII Corps]] under General [[Hasan Tahsin Pasha]] which included three divisions: the regular (''nizamiye'') [[22nd Infantry Division (Ottoman Empire)|22nd Division]] and the reserve (''redif'') Nasli\u00e7 and Ayd\u0131n Divisions{{sfn|Erickson|2003|p=170}} which, combined with the Ottoman garrisons in western Macedonia, totaled 35,000\u201340,000 men.{{sfn|Christopoulos|Bastias|1977|p=290}}\n\nThe Army of Thessaly crossed into Ottoman territory in the early morning hours of 5 October, finding most border posts to be abandoned, with the garrisons at Melouna Pass, Profitis Ilias and Tsouka resisting for several hours before retreating. The first major clashes took place the following day when the 1st and 2nd Greek Divisions attacked hastily organized defenses north of [[Elassona]]. Elassona was defended by three infantry battalions, two artillery batteries and half a squadron of cavalry.{{sfn|Christopoulos|Bastias|1977|p=290}} The battle for Elassona lasted for three hours, with the Ottomans retreating to avoid encirclement, thus giving the troops manning the main defensive line at Sarantaporo additional time to reinforce their positions.{{sfn|Kargakos|2012|pp=44\u201345}} The Greeks went on to advance {{convert|20|km|miles}} into the Elassona plateau without encountering any resistance.{{sfn|Kargakos|2012|p=47}} Between 7 and 8 October, Greek troops regrouped in front of Sarantaporo and dispatched cavalry reconnaissance patrols towards the Ottoman positions, locating the headquarters of the Ottoman VIII Corps at Hania Viglas and those of a reserve division at Glikovo.{{sfn|Christopoulos|Bastias|1977|p=290}}\n\nSituated between the Vigla and Amorves mountains, Sarantaporo was a narrow mountain pass, the only one connecting Thessaly with central Macedonia; it spanned some {{convert|7\u20138|km|miles|sigfig=1}}. Having ceded Thessaly to Greece in the [[Convention of Constantinople (1881)]], the Ottomans had been methodically reinforcing their positions around Sarantaporo in anticipation of a future war.{{sfn|Kargakos|2012|p=48}} The Ottomans had organized their defenses under the guidance of German military advisors, placing their artillery batteries and infantry in sheltered, camouflaged trenches on the ravine's steep slopes, allowing them to accurately fire along its entire length. Considered to be nearly impenetrable it was dubbed \"the graveyard of the Greek Army\" by  the Prussian Field Marshal [[Colmar Freiherr von der Goltz]].{{sfn|Dimitracopoulos|1992|p=42}}\n\n==Battle==\nAt 7 a.m. on 9 October, the Greek infantry began its assault on Sarantaporo. The 1st, 2nd and 3rd Divisions attacked the Ottoman main line frontally, their advance hampered by accurate Ottoman rifle and artillery fire and the ruggedness of the terrain. In the meantime, the 4th Division conducted a flanking maneuver from the west with the intention of occupying the Porta Pass, and striking the rear of the Ottoman positions.{{sfn|Christopoulos|Bastias|1977|p=291}} The 5th Division advanced further to the west towards the village of Zampourda which was situated on the other bank of the [[Haliacmon]] River, with the intention of protecting the left flank of the Greek forces emerging from the Sarantaporo pass. The cavalry brigade moved on the extreme west along the road towards [[Servia, Greece|Servia]], planning to block the bridge across the Haliacmon.{{sfn|Kargakos|2012|p=51}} Attacking from the east of the pass the Konstantinopoulos Evzone detachment overcame stiff resistance at Vlacholeivado and captured the village, but failing to advance further due to heavy fog.{{sfn|Christopoulos|Bastias|1977|p=291}}{{sfn|Apostolidis|1913|pp=207\u2013209}} At 2 p.m., the main bulk of the Greek artillery was brought to the main line, joining the engagement. Despite suffering heavy casualties, the three divisions had halted some {{convert|500-700|m|yards|sigfig=1}} from the Ottoman trenches intending to launch a final assault the following morning.{{sfn|Christopoulos|Bastias|1977|p=291}}\n\nThe 4th Division fought its way through the villages of Metaxas and Rachovo. Upon reaching the Porta Pass it engaged in a bloody clash with the defenders, securing its objective at 5 p.m.{{sfn|Kargakos|2012|p=53}} The 5th Division and the Gennadis Evzone detachment were confronted by four Ottoman reserve battalions at Lazarades which held their ground until sunset.{{sfn|Christopoulos|Bastias|1977|p=291}} The commander of the cavalry brigade ordered his unit to encamp at Loudani, refusing to advance further because of the resistance offered by the Ottomans at Lazarades. Fearing that they would be encircled by the Konstantinopoulos Evzone detachment, the Ottomans began to withdraw at 7 p.m., towards their second defensive line at Hani 739, under the cover of the night. Before retreating they fired a 20-minute artillery barrage on Greek positions along the entire frontline. Unaware of the Ottoman retreat the Greeks failed to use the opportunity and cut their access to the bridge across the Haliacmon. Upon reaching their second defensive line, the Ottomans became aware of the 4th Divisions' seizure of Porta Pass and panic spread in their ranks and many soldiers fled, abandoning their equipment.{{sfn|Apostolidis|1913|pp=203\u2013205}} On the morning of 10 October, the 4th Division charged down the northern slope of the Rahovo Mountain, surprising the Ottoman infantry and artillerymen who abandoned over twenty [[Krupp gun]]s and engaged in a disorganized retreat.{{sfn|Dimitracopoulos|1992|p=44}}{{sfn|Erickson|2003|pp=218\u2013219}} The Greek cavalry's indecision once again enabled the fleeing Ottomans to safely reach Servia and [[Kozani]].{{sfn|Kargakos|2012|pp=56\u201357}}\n\n==Aftermath==\nAt 4 p.m. on 10 October, the 4th Division entered Servia, witnessing 75 to 90 severed human heads belonging to local Christians lined up on either side of one of its streets.{{sfn|Dimitracopoulos|1992|p=44}}{{sfn|Christopoulos|Bastias|1977|p=292}} Following the declaration of war local authorities had detained all the Christian dignitaries from Servia and the surrounding villages with the intention of massacring them, a plan that was thwarted by Ottoman officer Omer Bey. However, upon realizing the imminent defeat of the Ottoman troops at Sarantaporo, the town's Muslim population massacred 117 local Christians.{{sfn|Kargakos|2012|pp=58\u201359}} By 11 October, the entirety of the Army of Thessaly had reached the banks of the Haliacmon, while the Greek cavalry entered Kozani unopposed,{{sfn|Christopoulos|Bastias|1977|p=292}} opening the way for the Greeks to advance towards the Greek majority city of [[Thessaloniki]] and assist the Serbs at [[Bitola|Monastir]].{{sfn|Dimitracopoulos|1992|p=46}} On 13 October, the Greek army transferred its general headquarters to Kozani; the following day King [[George I of Greece|George I]] arrived in the city, ordering the army to march towards Thessaloniki and [[Veroia]].{{sfn|Apostolidis|1913|pp=241\u2013243}} Greek casualties in the battle of Sarantaporo numbered 182 killed and over 1,000 wounded,{{sfn|Christopoulos|Bastias|1977|p=292}} while the Ottomans lost approximately 500 killed, 1,000 wounded, around 22 to 25 [[field artillery]] pieces captured and other significant material losses.{{sfn|Dimitracopoulos|1992|p=44}}{{sfn|Erickson|2003|pp=218\u2013219}}\n\nBy May 1913, the numerically inferior Ottomans had suffered a series of serious defeats to the League's armies on all fronts. The League had captured most of the Ottoman Empire's European territories and was rapidly approaching [[Constantinople]]. On 30 May, the two sides signed the [[Treaty of London (1913)|Treaty of London]] which granted the League's members all Ottoman lands west of [[Enos, Turkey|Enos]] on the [[Aegean Sea]] and north of [[K\u0131y\u0131k\u00f6y|Midia]] on the [[Black Sea]], as well as Crete. The fate of [[Independent Albania|Albania]] and the Ottoman-held Aegean islands was to be determined by the [[International relations of the Great Powers (1814\u20131919)|Great Powers]].{{sfn|Christopoulos|Bastias|1977|pp=330\u2013332}}\n\n==Notes==\n;Footnotes\n{{Reflist|group=Note}}\n\n;Citations\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==References==\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book |last=Apostolidis |first=Dimitrios |title=\u039f \u03bd\u03b9\u03ba\u03b7\u03c6\u03cc\u03c1\u03bf\u03c2 \u03b5\u03bb\u03bb\u03b7\u03bd\u03bf\u03c4\u03bf\u03c5\u03c1\u03ba\u03b9\u03ba\u03cc\u03c2 \u03c0\u03cc\u03bb\u03b5\u03bc\u03bf\u03c2 \u03c4\u03bf\u03c5 1912-1913|trans-title=The Victorious Greco-Turkish War of 1912-1913|volume=I|publisher=Estia|location=Athens|language=Greek|year=1913|url=https://anemi.lib.uoc.gr/metadata/8/d/1/metadata-9272bd94229998ed96a378ab0f986a22_1270023610.tkl|accessdate=13 November 2019|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Blackburn|first1=Bonnie|last2=Holford-Strevens|first2=Leofranc|title=The Oxford Companion to the Year|year=1999|publisher=Oxford University Press|location=Oxford|isbn=0-19-214231-3|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |first1=Georgios|last1=Christopoulos|first2=Ioannis|last2=Bastias|title=\u0399\u03c3\u03c4\u03bf\u03c1\u03af\u03b1 \u03c4\u03bf\u03c5 \u0395\u03bb\u03bb\u03b7\u03bd\u03b9\u03ba\u03bf\u03cd \u0395\u03b8\u03bd\u03bf\u03c5\u03c2: \u039d\u03b5\u03ce\u03c4\u03b5\u03c1\u03bf\u03c2 \u0395\u03bb\u03bb\u03b7\u03bd\u03b9\u03c3\u03bc\u03cc\u03c2 \u03b1\u03c0\u03bf \u03c4\u03bf 1881 \u03c9\u03c2 1913|trans-title=History of the Greek Nation: Modern Greece from 1881 until 1913 |volume=XIV |publisher=Ekdotiki Athinon|language=Greek|location=Athens|year=1977 |isbn=960-213-110-1|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Dimitracopoulos |first=Anastasios |title=The First Balkan War Through the Pages of Review L'Illustration |year=1992 |publisher=Hellenic Committee of Military History|location=Athens |oclc= 37043754| ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Erickson |first=Edward |title=Defeat in Detail: The Ottoman Army in the Balkans, 1912-1913 |year=2003|publisher=Praeger|location=Westport | isbn =978-0-275-97888-4| ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Hooton |first=Edward|title=Prelude to the First World War: The Balkan Wars 1912-1913 |year=2014|publisher=Fonthill Media|location=Stroud | isbn =978-1781551806  | ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Kargakos |first=Sarandos| title=\u0397 \u0395\u03bb\u03bb\u03ac\u03c2 \u03ba\u03b1\u03c4\u03ac \u03c4\u03bf\u03c5\u03c2 \u0392\u03b1\u03bb\u03ba\u03b1\u03bd\u03b9\u03ba\u03bf\u03cd\u03c2 \u03a0\u03bf\u03bb\u03ad\u03bc\u03bf\u03c5\u03c2 (1912-1913)|trans-title=Greece in the Balkan Wars (1912-1913)| publisher=Peritechnon|location=Athens| year = 2012 | isbn =978-960-8411-26-5|language=Greek| ref=harv}}\n* {{cite web |last=Katsikostas |first=Dimitrios |title=\u0397 \u03b1\u03bd\u03b1\u03b4\u03b9\u03bf\u03c1\u03b3\u03ac\u03bd\u03c9\u03c3\u03b7 \u03c4\u03c9\u03bd \u03b5\u03bd\u03cc\u03c0\u03bb\u03c9\u03bd \u03b4\u03c5\u03bd\u03ac\u03bc\u03b5\u03c9\u03bd \u03ba\u03b1\u03b9 \u03c4\u03bf \u03ad\u03c1\u03b3\u03bf \u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u03b3\u03b1\u03bb\u03bb\u03b9\u03ba\u03ae\u03c2 \u03c3\u03c4\u03c1\u03b1\u03c4\u03b9\u03c9\u03c4\u03b9\u03ba\u03ae\u03c2 \u03b1\u03c0\u03bf\u03c3\u03c4\u03bf\u03bb\u03ae\u03c2 Eydoux|trans-title=The Reorganization of the Armed Forces and the Efforts of the French Military Mission of Eydoux|publisher= Hellenic Army History Directorate |language=Greek|year= 2014 |url=https://dis.army.gr/sites/dis.army.gr/files/unmanaged/pdf/Articles_June14/Greek_French/ANADIORG_ED_APOST_EYDOUX.pdf|accessdate=13 November 2019 | ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal |last=Klapsis |first=Antonis |date=2009 |title=Between the Hammer and the Anvil. The Cyprus Question and the Greek Foreign Policy from the Treaty of Lausanne to the 1931 Revolt|url=https://hephaestus.nup.ac.cy/handle/11728/7388|journal=Modern Greek Studies Yearbook|volume=24 |pages=127\u2013140|access-date=9 April 2020|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal |first=Thanos|last=Veremis|title=The Officer Corps in Greece (1912\u20131936)|pages=113\u2013133|journal=Byzantine and Modern Greek Studies| volume =2|issue=1|year=1976|issn =0307-0131|publisher=Routledge|ref=harv}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sarantaporo 1912}}\n[[Category:Battles of the First Balkan War]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1912]]\n[[Category:Battles involving the Ottoman Empire]]\n[[Category:Battles involving Greece]]\n[[Category:1912 in Greece]]\n[[Category:1912 in the Ottoman Empire]]\n[[Category:Manastir Vilayet]]\n[[Category:Modern history of Thessaly]]\n[[Category:October 1912 events]]\n", "name_user": "Catlemur", "label": "safe", "comment": "ce", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Battle_of_Sarantaporo"}
{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in Maine", "text_new": "{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic in Maine, United States}}\n{{use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Maine\n| width           = \n| image           = \n| image_size      = \n| image_upright   = \n| alt             = \n| caption         = \n| map1            = \n| legend1         = \n| map2            = \n| legend2         = \n| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| map4            = \n| legend4         = \n| map5            = \n| legend5         = \n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[Maine]]\n| first_case      = [[Androscoggin County]]\n| arrival_date    = \n| origin          = \n| confirmed_cases = 867\n| suspected_cases = \n| severe_cases    = \n| recovery_cases  = 393\n| deaths          = 34\n| territories     = \n| total_ili       = \n| website         = {{URL|https://coronavirus.maine.gov/}}\n| hospitalized_cases = 136\n}}\n\nThe '''[[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]''' has reached the U.S. state of '''[[Maine]]'''. As of April 13, 2020, the Maine Department of Health and Human Services has confirmed 698 positive cases in the state, 111 of them had been hospitalized at some point and 246 of them have recovered. There have also been 19 deaths of patients with the virus, 11 of which were reported in Cumberland county, the remaining in Kennebec, Waldo, and York.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.maine.gov/dhhs/mecdc/infectious-disease/epi/airborne/coronavirus.shtml|title=Coronavirus {{!}} Airborne Disease Surveillance Epidemiology Program {{!}} MeCDC {{!}} Maine DHHS|website=www.maine.gov|access-date=2020-03-19|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200313203657/https://www.maine.gov/dhhs/mecdc/infectious-disease/epi/airborne/coronavirus.shtml|archive-date=March 13, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newscentermaine.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/maine-coronavirus-live-blog-update-what-mainers-need-to-know-about-covid-19/97-e06fc2a0-bdfd-4c56-b25d-933ba1e0ea51|title=Live Coronavirus Updates: 3 dead, 253 confirmed cases|website=WCSH|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/United States/Maine medical cases chart}}\n\n==Timeline==\nOn March 12, Maine Governor [[Janet Mills]] announced the state's first confirmed case of the coronavirus, a woman in her 50s in [[Androscoggin County]]. The woman is quarantined inside her home.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.foxnews.com/health/maine-confirms-first-coronavirus-case|title=Maine confirms first coronavirus case, patient is quarantined at home|first=Alexandria|last=Hein|date=March 12, 2020|publisher=Fox News Channel|accessdate=March 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Government response ==\nOn March 19, the City of Bangor announced that the Community Connector bus service would begin only allowing people to enter from the rear of the bus to encourage social distancing beginning on March 20. Passengers using walkers and wheelchairs were allowed to board from the front of the bus. As more social distancing practices were put into effect, the City of Bangor began using an honor system for the bus service and asked that passengers not occupy the seats directly behind the driver.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wabi.tv/content/news/Bangor-area-Community-Connector-bus-system-makes-changes-to-prevent-COVID-19-spread-568937261.html|title=Bangor area Community Connector bus system makes changes to prevent COVID-19 spread|last=Desk|first=News|website=www.wabi.tv|language=english|access-date=2020-03-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320025121/https://www.wabi.tv/content/news/Bangor-area-Community-Connector-bus-system-makes-changes-to-prevent-COVID-19-spread-568937261.html|archive-date=March 20, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/BangorCityHall/posts/10158389071314974|title=City of Bangor, Maine - City Hall|website=www.facebook.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref>\n\nOn March 24, the City of Portland announced that the manager has signed a stay-at-home order beginning on March 25 for all non-essential businesses and services in Portland, with a potential end date on April 27.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newscentermaine.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/portland-announces-stay-at-home-emergency-order/97-38eaa8b1-b331-4978-b07c-3907e8703257|title=Portland announces stay at home emergency order|website=WCSH|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\nOn March 26, the City of South Portland also announced a similar order beginning March 27 except for permitted activities.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pressherald.com/2020/03/26/south-portland-issues-stay-at-home-order/|title=South Portland issues stay-at-home order|last=Writer|first=Megan GrayStaff|date=2020-03-26|website=Press Herald|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\nOn March 30, Maine Governor [[Janet Mills]] issued \"a Stay Healthy at Home directive that requires people living in Maine to stay at home at all times unless for an essential job or an essential personal reason, such as obtaining food, medicine, health care, or other necessary purposes.\"<ref>https://www.maine.gov/governor/mills/news/governor-mills-issues-stay-healthy-home-mandate-2020-03-31.  Retrieved 2020-04-01.</ref>\n\nOn April 10,  Gov. Mills rescheduled Maine's congressional and legislative primary elections from June 9, 2020, to July 14.  Mills' executive order also expanded the ability to request absentee ballots, which may now be done up to and on election day.<ref>{{cite news|last=Andrews|first=Caitlin|date=December 18, 2019| url=https://bangordailynews.com/2020/04/10/politics/mills-officially-pushes-back-june-elections-to-july-14/ |title=Mills officially pushes back June elections to July 14|work=[[Bangor Daily News]]|accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Maine Department of Agriculture, Conservation, and Forestry closed 10 coastal state parks as overcrowding at those parks made social distancing difficult.  The Department said it would monitor the remaining state parks, most of which were still closed for the winter though walk-ins are permitted.<ref>{{cite news|last=Fleming|first=Deirdre|date=March 26, 2020| url=https://www.pressherald.com/2020/03/26/maine-closing-coastal-parks-and-beaches-amid-coronavirus-outbreak/ |title=Maine closing 10 state parks and beaches to stem tide of coronavirus|work=[[Portland Press Herald]]|accessdate=April 16, 2020}}</ref>  [[Baxter State Park]], a park independent of the state park system, announced it would close until at least July 1, only permitting walk-in day hikes. <ref>{{cite news|last=Fleming|first=Deirdre|date=April 15, 2020| url=https://www.centralmaine.com/2020/04/15/baxter-state-park-closes-to-camping-and-traffic/ |title=Baxter State Park shuts down camping and traffic|work=[[Kennebec Journal]]|accessdate=April 16, 2020}}</ref> [[Acadia National Park]] announced it would close indefinitely to prevent first responders from being exposed to the virus in the event of an injury and to prevent travel by visitors to the area.<ref>{{cite news|last=Hoey|first=Dennis|date=March 25, 2020| url=https://www.pressherald.com/2020/03/25/acadia-national-park-shutting-down-amid-coronavirus-outbreak/?rel=related&_ga=2.204644246.745502165.1587029692-446351361.1553029050|title=Acadia National Park shutting down amid coronavirus outbreak|work=[[Portland Press Herald]]|accessdate=April 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Impact on colleges and universities==\n===Public universities===\nThe [[University of Maine]] in [[Orono, Maine|Orono]] announced that in-person classes would be canceled for the remainder of the semester beginning March 23 and that all classes would be transitioned to online only. In addition, all students living on campus were required to be moved out by March 22.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://umaine.edu/emergency/coronavirus/|title=UMaine/UMM coronavirus response frequently asked questions, March 12 \u2013 Emergency Information \u2013 University of Maine|accessdate=March 13, 2020}}</ref>\n===Private universities===\n[[Bowdoin College]] announced on March 11 that students would not be permitted to return to campus from spring break and that the remainder of the semester would be conducted by remote learning.<ref>{{cite web|author=Griffin Stockford|url=https://www.newscentermaine.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/bowdoin-college-students-will-not-return-from-spring-break/97-ef5aee56-d604-4b10-8677-ea3304b0c1e9|title=Bowdoin College students will not return from spring break due to coronavirus concerns|date=March 11, 2020|accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref> As of March 25, four cases of coronavirus were confirmed among the campus community.<ref>{{cite web|author=Christopher Burns|url=https://bangordailynews.com/2020/03/25/news/midcoast/another-coronavirus-case-confirmed-at-bowdoin-college/|title=Another coronavirus case confirmed at Bowdoin College|date=March 25, 2020|accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Impact on transportation==\n===Highways===\nThe [[Maine Department of Transportation]] said that since the stay at home order issued by Gov. Mills, traffic on state roads had declined by double digits. This was the case especially in urban areas, though MDOT did not release specific figures as they were incomplete.<ref name=traffic>{{cite web|author=Peter McGuire|url=https://www.centralmaine.com/2020/03/24/plummeting-maine-turnpike-traffic-a-proxy-for-economic-collapse/|title=Plummeting Maine Turnpike traffic a \u2018proxy for economic collapse|date=March 24, 2020|accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Maine Turnpike]] Authority said it was paying all of its employees two weeks of administrative leave, and workers who continued to report to work would still be given it, effectively doubling their pay. A union leader called the arrangement \"good\" and said that worker's spirits were high as a result.<ref name=spirits>{{cite web|author=Scott Thistle|url=https://www.centralmaine.com/2020/03/19/toll-takers-taking-precautions-to-prevent-spread-of-virus/|title=Turnpike authority doubles pay to keep tollbooth workers on the job|date=March 19, 2020|accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref> The Authority announced that drivers uncomfortable with handing cash to a toll collector would not be penalized for using the [[EZ Pass]] only lanes and paying tolls online or by mail. A decision on waiving cash tolls would be made based on guidance from government health officials.<ref name=spirits />  Traffic counts had decreased by 20 percent in the immediate aftermath of the stay at home order, with weekend traffic falling 50 percent.  This decrease was due almost exclusively to declines in passenger cars using the road, as commercial traffic only declined 1 percent. It was unclear how the traffic decrease would affect the Turnpike's finances, though executive director [[Peter Mills (American politician)|Peter Mills]] said he would recommend to the Authority's board that they go ahead with a vote on a $28 million contract to widen five miles of the highway.<ref name=traffic />\n\n===Rail service===\nThe Northern New England Passenger Rail Authority announced a suspension of all remaining [[Amtrak]] ''[[Downeaster (train)|Downeaster]]'' service, to begin April 13th and last until April 30, after two prior service reductions.<ref>{{cite web|author=Mike Lowe|url=https://www.centralmaine.com/2020/04/11/downeaster-to-suspend-service-temporarily-starting-monday/|title=Downeaster to suspend service temporarily starting Monday|date=April 12, 2020|accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref>  On average, 20 passengers had been using the one remaining round trip to [[Boston]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Fred Bever|url=https://www.mainepublic.org/post/downeaster-train-service-suspended-after-daily-ridership-falls-20-passengers|title=Downeaster Train Service Suspended After Daily Ridership Falls To 20 Passengers|date=April 13, 2020|accessdate=April 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Air travel===\nBoardings at the [[Portland International Jetport]] dropped by 70 percent compared to the prior year for the week ending March 21.<ref name=traffic />\n\n==Statistics==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:right\"\n! colspan=\"5\" |2019 Novel Coronavirus (COVID-19) Cases in Maine<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web | url=https://www.maine.gov/dhhs/mecdc/infectious-disease/epi/airborne/coronavirus.shtml |title = Novel Coronavirus 2019 (COVID-19) &#124; Airborne Disease Surveillance Epidemiology Program &#124; MeCDC &#124; Maine DHHS}}</ref>\nUpdated April 15, 2020\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" |County\n! scope=\"col\" |Confirmed Cases*\n!Recovered\n!Hospitalizations\n!Deaths\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Androscoggin County, Maine|Androscoggin]]\n|35\n|16\n|11\n|1\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Aroostook County, Maine|Aroostook]]\n|2\n|1\n|0\n|0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Cumberland County, Maine|Cumberland]]\n|378\n|196\n|58\n|16\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Franklin County, Maine|Franklin]]\n|12\n|4\n|1\n|0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Hancock County, Maine|Hancock]]\n|6\n|1\n|1\n|0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Kennebec County, Maine|Kennebec]]\n|97\n|16\n|14\n|4\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Knox County, Maine|Knox]]\n|12\n|6\n|1\n|0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Lincoln County, Maine|Lincoln]]\n|12\n|7\n|0\n|0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Oxford County, Maine|Oxford]]\n|14\n|9\n|1\n|0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Penobscot County, Maine|Penobscot]]\n|43\n|27\n|8\n|0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Piscataquis County, Maine|Piscataquis]]\n|1\n|1\n|0\n|0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Sagadahoc County, Maine|Sagadahoc]]\n|16\n|9\n|5\n|0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Somerset County, Maine|Somerset]]\n|16\n|4\n|0\n|0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Waldo County, Maine|Waldo]]\n|42\n|5\n|1\n|7\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Washington County, Maine|Washington]]\n|2\n|2\n|0\n|0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[York County, Maine|York]]\n|177\n|89\n|35\n|6\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |Unknown\n|1\n|0\n|0\n|0\n|- class=\"sortbottom\"\n! style=\"text-align:right;\" |Total\n! style=\"text-align:right;\" |867\n! style=\"text-align:right;\" |393\n! style=\"text-align:right;\" |136\n! style=\"text-align:right;\" |34\n|}\n<nowiki>*</nowiki>includes both confirmed and presumptive positive cases\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.maine.gov/governor/mills/covid-19 Information from the Governor's Office]\n* [https://www.maine.gov/dhhs/mecdc/infectious-disease/epi/airborne/coronavirus.shtml Coronavirus information] from the [https://www.maine.gov/dhhs/ Maine Department of Health and Human Services].\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States}}\n{{Portal bar|Maine|Medicine|Viruses|Coronavirus disease 2019|Pandemic}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States by state|Maine]]\n[[Category:2020 in Maine|coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:Disasters in Maine]]\n[[Category:Health in Maine]]\n[[Category:March 2020 events in the United States|coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:April 2020 events in the United States|coronavirus pandemic]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic in Maine, United States}}\n{{use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Maine\n| width           = \n| image           = \n| image_size      = \n| image_upright   = \n| alt             = \n| caption         = \n| map1            = \n| legend1         = \n| map2            = \n| legend2         = \n| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| map4            = \n| legend4         = \n| map5            = \n| legend5         = \n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[Maine]]\n| first_case      = [[Androscoggin County]]\n| arrival_date    = \n| origin          = \n| confirmed_cases = 867\n| suspected_cases = \n| severe_cases    = \n| recovery_cases  = 393\n| deaths          = 34\n| territories     = \n| total_ili       = \n| website         = {{URL|https://coronavirus.maine.gov/}}\n| hospitalized_cases = 136\n}}\n\nThe '''[[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]''' has reached the U.S. state of '''[[Maine]]'''. As of April 13, 2020, the Maine Department of Health and Human Services has confirmed 698 positive cases in the state, 111 of them had been hospitalized at some point and 246 of them have recovered. There have also been 19 deaths of patients with the virus, 11 of which were reported in Cumberland county, the remaining in Kennebec, Waldo, and York.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.maine.gov/dhhs/mecdc/infectious-disease/epi/airborne/coronavirus.shtml|title=Coronavirus {{!}} Airborne Disease Surveillance Epidemiology Program {{!}} MeCDC {{!}} Maine DHHS|website=www.maine.gov|access-date=2020-03-19|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200313203657/https://www.maine.gov/dhhs/mecdc/infectious-disease/epi/airborne/coronavirus.shtml|archive-date=March 13, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newscentermaine.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/maine-coronavirus-live-blog-update-what-mainers-need-to-know-about-covid-19/97-e06fc2a0-bdfd-4c56-b25d-933ba1e0ea51|title=Live Coronavirus Updates: 3 dead, 253 confirmed cases|website=WCSH|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/United States/Maine medical cases chart}}\n\n==Timeline==\nOn March 12, Maine Governor [[Janet Mills]] announced the state's first confirmed case of the coronavirus, a woman in her 50s in [[Androscoggin County]]. The woman is quarantined inside her home.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.foxnews.com/health/maine-confirms-first-coronavirus-case|title=Maine confirms first coronavirus case, patient is quarantined at home|first=Alexandria|last=Hein|date=March 12, 2020|publisher=Fox News Channel|accessdate=March 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Government response ==\nOn March 19, the City of Bangor announced that the Community Connector bus service would begin only allowing people to enter from the rear of the bus to encourage social distancing beginning on March 20. Passengers using walkers and wheelchairs were allowed to board from the front of the bus. As more social distancing practices were put into effect, the City of Bangor began using an honor system for the bus service and asked that passengers not occupy the seats directly behind the driver.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wabi.tv/content/news/Bangor-area-Community-Connector-bus-system-makes-changes-to-prevent-COVID-19-spread-568937261.html|title=Bangor area Community Connector bus system makes changes to prevent COVID-19 spread|last=Desk|first=News|website=www.wabi.tv|language=english|access-date=2020-03-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320025121/https://www.wabi.tv/content/news/Bangor-area-Community-Connector-bus-system-makes-changes-to-prevent-COVID-19-spread-568937261.html|archive-date=March 20, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/BangorCityHall/posts/10158389071314974|title=City of Bangor, Maine - City Hall|website=www.facebook.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref>\n\nOn March 24, the City of Portland announced that the manager has signed a stay-at-home order beginning on March 25 for all non-essential businesses and services in Portland, with a potential end date on April 27.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newscentermaine.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/portland-announces-stay-at-home-emergency-order/97-38eaa8b1-b331-4978-b07c-3907e8703257|title=Portland announces stay at home emergency order|website=WCSH|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\nOn March 26, the City of South Portland also announced a similar order beginning March 27 except for permitted activities.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pressherald.com/2020/03/26/south-portland-issues-stay-at-home-order/|title=South Portland issues stay-at-home order|last=Writer|first=Megan GrayStaff|date=2020-03-26|website=Press Herald|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\nOn March 30, Maine Governor [[Janet Mills]] issued \"a Stay Healthy at Home directive that requires people living in Maine to stay at home at all times unless for an essential job or an essential personal reason, such as obtaining food, medicine, health care, or other necessary purposes.\"<ref>https://www.maine.gov/governor/mills/news/governor-mills-issues-stay-healthy-home-mandate-2020-03-31.  Retrieved 2020-04-01.</ref>\n\nOn April 10,  Gov. Mills rescheduled Maine's congressional and legislative primary elections from June 9, 2020, to July 14.  Mills' executive order also expanded the ability to request absentee ballots, which may now be done up to and on election day.<ref>{{cite news|last=Andrews|first=Caitlin|date=December 18, 2019| url=https://bangordailynews.com/2020/04/10/politics/mills-officially-pushes-back-june-elections-to-july-14/ |title=Mills officially pushes back June elections to July 14|work=[[Bangor Daily News]]|accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Maine Department of Agriculture, Conservation, and Forestry closed 10 coastal state parks as overcrowding at those parks made social distancing difficult.  The Department said it would monitor the remaining state parks, most of which were still closed for the winter though walk-ins are permitted.<ref>{{cite news|last=Fleming|first=Deirdre|date=March 26, 2020| url=https://www.pressherald.com/2020/03/26/maine-closing-coastal-parks-and-beaches-amid-coronavirus-outbreak/ |title=Maine closing 10 state parks and beaches to stem tide of coronavirus|work=[[Portland Press Herald]]|accessdate=April 16, 2020}}</ref>  [[Baxter State Park]], a park independent of the state park system, announced it would close until at least July 1, only permitting walk-in day hikes. <ref>{{cite news|last=Fleming|first=Deirdre|date=April 15, 2020| url=https://www.centralmaine.com/2020/04/15/baxter-state-park-closes-to-camping-and-traffic/ |title=Baxter State Park shuts down camping and traffic|work=[[Kennebec Journal]]|accessdate=April 16, 2020}}</ref> [[Acadia National Park]] announced it would close indefinitely to prevent first responders from being exposed to the virus in the event of an injury and to prevent travel by visitors to the area.<ref>{{cite news|last=Hoey|first=Dennis|date=March 25, 2020| url=https://www.pressherald.com/2020/03/25/acadia-national-park-shutting-down-amid-coronavirus-outbreak/?rel=related&_ga=2.204644246.745502165.1587029692-446351361.1553029050|title=Acadia National Park shutting down amid coronavirus outbreak|work=[[Portland Press Herald]]|accessdate=April 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Impact on colleges and universities==\n===Public universities===\nThe [[University of Maine]] in [[Orono, Maine|Orono]] announced that in-person classes would be canceled for the remainder of the semester beginning March 23 and that all classes would be transitioned to online only. In addition, all students living on campus were required to be moved out by March 22.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://umaine.edu/emergency/coronavirus/|title=UMaine/UMM coronavirus response frequently asked questions, March 12 \u2013 Emergency Information \u2013 University of Maine|accessdate=March 13, 2020}}</ref>\n===Private universities===\n[[Bowdoin College]] announced on March 11 that students would not be permitted to return to campus from spring break and that the remainder of the semester would be conducted by remote learning.<ref>{{cite web|author=Griffin Stockford|url=https://www.newscentermaine.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/bowdoin-college-students-will-not-return-from-spring-break/97-ef5aee56-d604-4b10-8677-ea3304b0c1e9|title=Bowdoin College students will not return from spring break due to coronavirus concerns|date=March 11, 2020|accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref> As of March 25, four cases of coronavirus were confirmed among the campus community.<ref>{{cite web|author=Christopher Burns|url=https://bangordailynews.com/2020/03/25/news/midcoast/another-coronavirus-case-confirmed-at-bowdoin-college/|title=Another coronavirus case confirmed at Bowdoin College|date=March 25, 2020|accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Impact on transportation==\n===Highways===\nThe [[Maine Department of Transportation]] said that since the stay at home order issued by Gov. Mills, traffic on state roads had declined by double digits. This was the case especially in urban areas, though MDOT did not release specific figures as they were incomplete.<ref name=traffic>{{cite web|author=Peter McGuire|url=https://www.centralmaine.com/2020/03/24/plummeting-maine-turnpike-traffic-a-proxy-for-economic-collapse/|title=Plummeting Maine Turnpike traffic a \u2018proxy for economic collapse|date=March 24, 2020|accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Maine Turnpike]] Authority said it was paying all of its employees two weeks of administrative leave, and workers who continued to report to work would still be given it, effectively doubling their pay. A union leader called the arrangement \"good\" and said that worker's spirits were high as a result.<ref name=spirits>{{cite web|author=Scott Thistle|url=https://www.centralmaine.com/2020/03/19/toll-takers-taking-precautions-to-prevent-spread-of-virus/|title=Turnpike authority doubles pay to keep tollbooth workers on the job|date=March 19, 2020|accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref> The Authority announced that drivers uncomfortable with handing cash to a toll collector would not be penalized for using the [[EZ Pass]] only lanes and paying tolls online or by mail. A decision on waiving cash tolls would be made based on guidance from government health officials.<ref name=spirits />  Traffic counts had decreased by 20 percent in the immediate aftermath of the stay at home order, with weekend traffic falling 50 percent.  This decrease was due almost exclusively to declines in passenger cars using the road, as commercial traffic only declined 1 percent. It was unclear how the traffic decrease would affect the Turnpike's finances, though executive director [[Peter Mills (American politician)|Peter Mills]] said he would recommend to the Authority's board that they go ahead with a vote on a $28 million contract to widen five miles of the highway.<ref name=traffic />\n\n===Rail service===\nThe Northern New England Passenger Rail Authority announced a suspension of all remaining [[Amtrak]] ''[[Downeaster (train)|Downeaster]]'' service, to begin April 13th and last until April 30, after two prior service reductions.<ref>{{cite web|author=Mike Lowe|url=https://www.centralmaine.com/2020/04/11/downeaster-to-suspend-service-temporarily-starting-monday/|title=Downeaster to suspend service temporarily starting Monday|date=April 12, 2020|accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref>  On average, 20 passengers had been using the one remaining round trip to [[Boston]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Fred Bever|url=https://www.mainepublic.org/post/downeaster-train-service-suspended-after-daily-ridership-falls-20-passengers|title=Downeaster Train Service Suspended After Daily Ridership Falls To 20 Passengers|date=April 13, 2020|accessdate=April 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Air travel===\nBoardings at the [[Portland International Jetport]] dropped by 70 percent compared to the prior year for the week ending March 21.<ref name=traffic />\n\n==Statistics==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:right\"\n! colspan=\"5\" |2019 Novel Coronavirus (COVID-19) Cases in Maine<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web | url=https://www.maine.gov/dhhs/mecdc/infectious-disease/epi/airborne/coronavirus.shtml |title = Novel Coronavirus 2019 (COVID-19) &#124; Airborne Disease Surveillance Epidemiology Program &#124; MeCDC &#124; Maine DHHS}}</ref>\nUpdated April 15, 2020\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" |County\n! scope=\"col\" |Confirmed Cases*\n!Recovered\n!Hospitalizations\n!Deaths\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Androscoggin County, Maine|Androscoggin]]\n|35\n|16\n|11\n|1\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Aroostook County, Maine|Aroostook]]\n|2\n|1\n|0\n|0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Cumberland County, Maine|Cumberland]]\n|378\n|196\n|58\n|16\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Franklin County, Maine|Franklin]]\n|12\n|4\n|1\n|0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Hancock County, Maine|Hancock]]\n|6\n|1\n|1\n|0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Kennebec County, Maine|Kennebec]]\n|97\n|16\n|14\n|4\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Knox County, Maine|Knox]]\n|12\n|6\n|1\n|0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Lincoln County, Maine|Lincoln]]\n|12\n|7\n|0\n|0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Oxford County, Maine|Oxford]]\n|14\n|9\n|1\n|0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Penobscot County, Maine|Penobscot]]\n|43\n|27\n|8\n|0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Piscataquis County, Maine|Piscataquis]]\n|1\n|1\n|0\n|0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Sagadahoc County, Maine|Sagadahoc]]\n|16\n|9\n|5\n|0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Somerset County, Maine|Somerset]]\n|16\n|4\n|0\n|0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Waldo County, Maine|Waldo]]\n|42\n|5\n|1\n|5\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Washington County, Maine|Washington]]\n|2\n|2\n|0\n|0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[York County, Maine|York]]\n|177\n|89\n|35\n|6\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |Unknown\n|1\n|0\n|0\n|2\n|- class=\"sortbottom\"\n! style=\"text-align:right;\" |Total\n! style=\"text-align:right;\" |867\n! style=\"text-align:right;\" |393\n! style=\"text-align:right;\" |136\n! style=\"text-align:right;\" |34\n|}\n<nowiki>*</nowiki>includes both confirmed and presumptive positive cases\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.maine.gov/governor/mills/covid-19 Information from the Governor's Office]\n* [https://www.maine.gov/dhhs/mecdc/infectious-disease/epi/airborne/coronavirus.shtml Coronavirus information] from the [https://www.maine.gov/dhhs/ Maine Department of Health and Human Services].\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States}}\n{{Portal bar|Maine|Medicine|Viruses|Coronavirus disease 2019|Pandemic}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States by state|Maine]]\n[[Category:2020 in Maine|coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:Disasters in Maine]]\n[[Category:Health in Maine]]\n[[Category:March 2020 events in the United States|coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:April 2020 events in the United States|coronavirus pandemic]]\n", "name_user": "Zanchi", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eStatistics", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_Maine"}
{"title_page": "French cutter Mutin (1778)", "text_new": "{{other ships|French ship Mutin|HMS Mutine|HMS Pigmy}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2017}}\n{|{{Infobox ship begin}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n|Ship image=\n|Ship caption=\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n|Hide header=\n|Ship country=France\n|Ship flag=[[File:Flag of the Kingdom of France (1814-1830).svg|45px|border|French Navy Ensign]] \n|Ship name=''Mutin''\n|Ship namesake=\n|Ship ordered=\n|Ship builder=Dunkirk\n|Ship laid down=June 1778\n|Ship launched=November 1778\n|Ship acquired=\n|Ship commissioned=\n|Ship decommissioned=\n|Ship in service=\n|Ship out of service=\n|Ship captured=2 October 1779\n|Ship struck=\n|Ship reinstated=\n|Ship fate=\n|Ship status=\n|Ship honours=\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n|Hide header=title\n|Ship country=[[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland|UK]]\n|Ship flag=[[File:Naval Ensign of the United Kingdom.svg|60px|Royal Navy Ensign]]\n|Ship name=HMS ''Mutine''\n|Ship ordered=\n|Ship builder=\n|Ship laid down=\n|Ship launched=\n|Ship acquired=2 October 1779 by capture\n|Ship commissioned=\n|Ship decommissioned=\n|Ship in service=\n|Ship out of service=\n|Ship renamed=HMS ''Pigmy'' 20 January 1798\n|Ship struck=\n|Ship reinstated=\n|Ship honours=[[Naval General Service Medal (1847)|Naval General Service Medal]] with clasp \"Egypt\"<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=21077|pages=791\u2013792|date=15 March 1850}}</ref>\n|Ship captured=\n|Ship fate=Wrecked 10&nbsp;August&nbsp;1805\n|Ship status=\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n|Hide header=\n|Header caption={{sfnp|Winfield|2008|p=354}} \n|Ship class=[[Mutin class cutter|''Mutin''-class cutter]]\n|Ship type=[[Cutter (ship)|Cutter]]\n|Ship tonnage=\n|Ship displacement=\n|Ship tons burthen=215{{small|{{frac|9|94}}}} ([[Builder's Old Measurement|bm]])\n|Ship length=*Overall:&nbsp;{{convert|76|ft|11+1/4|in|m|1|abbr=on}} \n*Keel:&nbsp;{{convert|59|ft|5+1/4|in|m|1|abbr=on}}\n|Ship beam={{convert|26|ft|1|in|m|1|abbr=on}}\n|Ship height=\n|Ship draught=\n|Ship hold depth={{convert|10|ft|1|in|m|1|abbr=on}}\n|Ship sail plan=\n|Ship speed=\n|Ship endurance=\n|Ship boats=\n|Ship capacity=\n|Ship troops=\n|Ship complement=*French service: 84 (but 120 at capture)\n*British service:70\n|Ship crew=\n|Ship armament=*French service: 14 guns\n*British service: 14 x 4-pounder guns + 10 x \u00bd-pounder [[swivel gun]]s\n|Ship armour=\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n|}\n'''''Mutin''''' was a 14-gun [[Cutter (ship)|cutter]] of the [[French Navy]], the lead ship of the [[Mutin-class cutter|''Mutin'' Class]] of five naval cutters. She was launched in 1778 and the [[Royal Navy]] captured her the next year, taking her into service as HMS ''Mutine''. The Royal Navy renamed her HMS ''Pigmy'' in 1798. She was lost in 1805.\n\n== Career ==\nOn 17 August 1779 ''Mutin'' accepted the surrender of the British cutter {{HMS|Active|1779|2}} in the Channel. ''Active'' had encountered the combined Franco-Spanish fleet in the [[English Channel]] and was unable to escape.{{sfnp|Hepper|1994|p=56}}\n\n[[HMS Jupiter (1778)|HMS ''Jupiter'']] captured ''Mutin'', along with her sister [[French ship Pilote (1779)|''Pilote'']], on 2 October after having dismasted ''Mutin'' by gunfire.{{sfnp|Demerliac|1996|p=87, #574}} At the time of her capture ''Mutin'' was under the command of Chevalier de Roquefieul.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=12020|page=2|date=5 October 1779}}</ref>\n\n===Royal Navy service===\nBetween 16 November 1779 and 13 December 1780, she was at Portsmouth, being fitted. The Royal Navy named and registered her as HMS ''Mutine'' on 22 January 1780.{{sfnp|Winfield|2008|p=354}} Lieutenant Samuel Cox commissioned her in October 1779 for the North Sea.\n\n''Mutine'' shared with His Majesty's cutters {{HMS|Rambler|1778|2}} and {{HMS|Griffin|1778|2}} in the capture on 30 December 1780 of the French privateer ''General Ville Pateaux''.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=12171|page=2|date=17 March 1781}}</ref>\n\nFrom March 1782 she was under the command of Lieutenant James Hills. On 6 October she captured the French privateer [[lugger]]  ''Compte de Valentinois'' and delivered it to Admiralty control at Spithead.<ref>{{cite news| title =Captures By British men of war | work =The Scots Magazine | page =52 | publisher = | date =1 December 1782 | url =http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/BL/0000545/17821201/012/0052?browse=true | accessdate =1 November 2015 }}</ref> ''Count de Valentinois'' was armed with two 3-pounder guns and eight swivel guns. She had a crew of 31 men under the command of Captain Le Dos and had sailed from Cherbourg the previous evening. She had captured nothing prior to encountering ''Mutine''.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=12378|page=1|date=8 October 1782}}</ref> \n\nIn May 1783 Lieutenant Robert Watson replaced Hills. Watson remained in command until ''Mutine'' was [[paid off]] in 1787 and transferred to [[Plymouth Dockyard]] for repairs. There was no work on the ship until 1789, when she underwent an extensive refit at a cost of \u00a33,884.{{sfnp|Winfield|2007|p=336}}{{refn|This equates to a relative value of \u00a3426,400 in 2014 terms.<ref>{{cite web| title =Purchasing Power of British Pounds from 1264 to Present | publisher =MeasuringWorth | date=2015 | url =http://www.measuringworth.com/ukcompare/result.php?year_source=1789&amount=3884&year_result=2014| accessdate =1 November 2015}}</ref>|group=Note}} \n\n''Mutine'' was recommissioned in October 1789 under Lieutenant Humphrey West and detailed for Mediterranean service in 1790. From July 1795 she was assigned to the squadron led by Admiral [[Horatio Nelson]], then in position off the coast of Genoa.{{sfnp|Winfield|2007|p=336}}\n\n===French Revolutionary Wars===\nIn January 1797 Lieutenant William Shepheard replaced West. ''Mutine'' was renamed ''Pigmy'' in 1798. She shared with {{HMS|Arethusa|1793|2}}, {{HMS|Netley|1798|2}} and the cutter {{HMS|Trial|1793|2}} in the proceeds from the detention of two vessels under neutral colours, ''Federick Molk'' and ''Vrow Judith'', on 18 and 21 August.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=15487|page=601|date=8 June 1802}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 January 1799, at noon, ''Pigmy'' was two miles SE of [[Durlston Bay|Durlston Head]] when she sighted a cutter and two brigs. ''Pigmy'' gave chase and at 1:40 succeeded in recapturing the two brigs, ''Lark'' and ''Dion''. After securing these two vessels ''Pigmy'' continued the chase with the result that at 4pm she succeeded in capturing the French privateer cutter ''Rancune''. ''Rancune'' was armed with two [[swivel gun]]s and had a crew of 21 men under the command of Antoine Fran\u00e7ois Victor Joseph Panpeville. She was 26 hours out of Cherbourg and the two brigs were her sole captures. ''Lark'', Francis Artis, master, was sailing from Cardiff to London with a cargo of bar iron. ''Dion'', Esdras Best, master, was on the same route and with the same cargo.captured the French privateer ''Rancune''.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=15097|pages=36\u201337||date=9 January 1799}}</ref>  For the remainder of the year, ''Pygmy'' operated in [[Quiberon Bay]] supporting the Royalist by bringing arms and money.<ref name=Marshall>Marshall (1829), Supplement, Part 3, pp.21-23.</ref>\n\n''Pigmy'' shared with {{HMS|Anson|1781|2}}, {{HMS|Boadicea|1797|2}}, {{HMS|Severn|1786|2}}, and {{HMS|Sheerness|1787|2}}, and the [[hired armed vessels|hired armed]] cutter [[Hired armed cutter Telemachus|''Telemachus'']] in the capture of four vessels:<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=15301|page=1176|date=11 October 1800}}</ref>\n*''St Francois'', taken 25 December 1799;\n*''St Pierre de Carnac'', taken 12 January 1800;\n*a brig of unknown name, taken 17 January 1800; and\n*''Anna Louisa'', taken 22 January 1800.\n\nIn May 1800 ''Pigmy'' was part of the Royal Navy squadron assisting at the [[Siege of Genoa (1800)|siege of Genoa]]. She shared with numerous other British vessels in the proceeds of the row galley cut out by their boats on 21 May,<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=15821|page=869|date=2 July 1805}}</ref> the capture on 23 May of the ''St Jean Baptiste'',<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=15820|page=851|date=29 June 1805}}</ref> the capture of the ketch [[French brig Albanaise (1790)|''Albanaise'']] on 4 June that the Royal Navy took into service, and the surrender of the city that same day.<ref>{{London Gazette|date=16 July 1805|issue=15825|page=933}}</ref>{{refn|A petty officer's share of the prize money for ''Albanaise'' was worth 7[[shilling|s]] 4[[pence|d]]; a seaman's share was worth 1s 3d. There was also an allocation of prize money for sundry vessels carrying corn that came into Genoa between 4 and 16 June. A petty officer's share of the prize money was worth 3s 6d; a seaman's share was worth 8d.<ref>{{London Gazette|date=11 April 1809|issue=16246|page=505}}</ref>|group=Note}}\n\nOn 20 July 1800, ''Pigmy'' was in company {{HMS|Speedy|1782|2}}, under the command of [[Thomas Cochrane, 10th Earl of Dundonald|Lord Cochrane]], in the Mediterranean. They captured the Imperial [[tartane]] ''Madonna Moseti Petro'', which was sailing to Cabrera with a cargo of wood.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=15301|page=1170|date=11 October 1800}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 August 1800, the brig {{HMS|Corso|1796|2}}, Lieutenant W. Ricketts, commander, and  ''Pigmy'' were at [[Cesenatico]]. Their orders were to destroy the vessels in its harbour, and \"make a proper example of the town.\" The British were unable to approach closely enough so during the night of 30 August Ricketts sent in boats of both vessels under the overall command of Lieutenant [[James Lucas Yeo]], first lieutenant of ''Corso''. The attackers were able to capture the town, sink two boats, and burn 11 others. One of the sunken vessels was deeply laden with copper, money, and bale goods. Four of the vessels sank in the mouth of the harbour, and fire consumed both piers. The British sailors were able to hold off some French infantry, but when Ricketts observed French cavalry approaching he ordered the boats to withdraw.<ref name=LG15301>{{London Gazette|issue=15301|pages=1171\u20131172|date=11 October 1800}}</ref>\n\nAfterwards, Ricketts sent the authorities of the town the following note:<ref name=LG15301/>\n<blockquote>To the Inhabitants of Cesenatico.\nThe Treachery of your Municipality, in causing to be arrested an Officer with Dispatches, has been long known to the British Admiral in these Seas. That Municipality may now sadly know that the Severity of Judgment, long delayed, is always exemplary. That the Innocent suffer with the Guilty, though much to be regretted, is the natural Feature of War; and the more terrible Infliction on this occasion, the more striking the Example should prove to surrounding Municipalities.\n(Signed) W. RICKETTS</blockquote>\n\nFrom September 1800 to June 1801, ''Pygmy'', alone or with ''Corso'', captured several small vessels, some of them armed:<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=15428|pages=1383\u20131386|date=17 November 1801}}</ref>\n\n*French [[trabaccolo]] privateer ''Bataglia di Marengo'', while on a cruise from [[Ravenna]] (6 September);\n*Imperial trabaccalo ''Divine Providence'', sailing from Cesenatriro to France with a cargo of rope (17 September);\n*Neapolitan [[polacca]] brig ''Madona de Laura'', sailing from Trepano to Ponto Gai with a cargo of salt (20 September);\n*Imperial trabaccolo ''Divine Providence'', sailing from [[Monopoli]] to Milan with a cargo of oil (6 October);\n*Cisalpine trabaccolo sailing from Ravenna to [[Pesaro]] with a cargo of oil (16 November, with ''Corso'');   \n*Cisalpine trabacolo, from Ravenna bound to Pesaro, in ballast (16 November, with ''Corso'');\n*Imperial ship ''Seinge'', sailing from Barcelona to Trieste with a cargo of brandy (17 January 1801, with ''Corso'');\n*Russian polacca ship ''Madona Turgliana'', sailing from the Morea to Trieste with a cargo of leather (17 January, with ''Corso'');{{refn|''Seinge'' is probably ''Strange'', which ''Corso'' captured that day.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=15506|page=861|date=14 August 1802}}</ref>|group=Note}}\n*Danish ship ''Adonis'', detained while sailing from Copenhagen to Trieste with a cargo of stockfish (13 February, with ''Corso'');\n*Danish brig ''Madellina Christiana'', detained while sailing from Venice to [[Zante]] with a cargo of planks (16 February, with ''Corso'');\n*French trabaccolo ''Ad\u00e9la\u00efde'' (see below);\n*Imperial trabaccolo ''Madona del Anunciade'', sailing from Trieste to Fiume with a cargo of hemp (27 February, with ''Corso'');\n*French trabaccolo privateer ''Achille'' (15 March, see below, with ''Corso''); and\n*French brig ''Prudente'', of two guns and 36 men, sailing from Toulon to Alexandria, with a cargo of ammunition, artificers' tools, and \"Comedians\" (8  June).(Apparently ''Prudente'' had some 100 passengers aboard, including troops, and actual comedians.)<ref name=Marshall/>\n\nThe deputies of the Mercantile Insurance Company in Trieste presented Shepheard with a golden snuffbox on 5 January as an expression of their appreciation for his efforts in suppressing \"piratical enemies\" in the upper Adriatic.<ref name=Marshall/>\n\nOn 18 February 1801, ''Pigmy'' captured the French privateer ''Ad\u00e9la\u00efde''. ''Ad\u00e9la\u00efde'' had been a fishing trabaccolo before her conversion to privateer. She was armed with one 6-pounder and two 12-pounder guns, and had a crew of 51 men under the command of Dominique Cannilla. She was seven days out of Ancona and had taken one small prize.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=15350|page=362|date=31 March 1801}}</ref> On 26 February ''Pigmy'' captured the ''Madona Turliana''.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=16192|page=1416|date=15 October 1808}}</ref>\n\nThen on the morning of 16 March ''Pigmy'' was on the north side of \"Isle Lonzo'\" when she sighted and gave chase to another trabaccolo. About two hours later this vessel anchored near the \"Isle Molata\", hoisted French colours, fired one shot, and then [[striking the colours|struck]]. She proved to be the privateer ''Achille'', of four 9-pounder and two brass 6-pounder guns. She had a crew of 44 men and was one day out of Ancona. She had not taken any prizes.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=15359|page=465|date=28 April 1801}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 April ''Corso'' and ''Pigmy'' captured the ''St Luigi''.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=16180|page=1233|date=6 September 1808}}</ref>\n\n''Pigmy'' was among the many vessels that shared in the proceeds of the capture on 9 June of the ''Felicit\u00e9'' and ''Josephine'' off Alexandria.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=15929|page=772|date=27 June 1806}}</ref>\n\nThe next day, ''Pigmy'' spoke with {{HMS|Swiftsure|1787|2}} and warned Captain [[Benjamin Hallowell Carew|Benjamin Hallowell]] that a French squadron under Admiral [[Honor\u00e9 Joseph Antoine Ganteaume|Ganteaume]] had put to sea. ''Swiftsure'' and the French encountered each other on 24 June, with the result that ''Swiftsure'' was forced to strike.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=15437|pages=1505\u20131506|date=19 December 1801}}</ref>\n\n{{main|Action of 24 June 1801}}\n\nBecause ''Pigmy'' served in the navy's Egyptian campaign between 8 March and 2 September, her officers and crew qualified for the clasp \"Egypt\" to the Naval General Service Medal that the [[Admiralty]] authorised in 1850 for all surviving claimants.{{#tag:ref|A first-class share of the prize money awarded in April 1823 was worth [[\u00a3sd|\u00a3]]34 2[[shilling|s]] 4[[pence|d]]; a fifth-class share, that of a seaman, was worth 3s 11\u00bdd. The amount was small as the total had to be shared between 79 vessels and the entire army contingent.<ref>{{London Gazette|page=633 |issue=17915|date=3 April 1823}}</ref>|group=Note}}\n\nOn 18 September, ''Pigmy'' captured the Ottoman polacca ''St Michele''.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=15533|page=1214|date=16 November 1802}}</ref> ''Pigmy'' shared with {{HMS|Pomone|1794|2}}, {{HMS|Vincejo|1799|2}}, and the privateer ''Furioso'' in the proceeds of the capture on 2 October of the ''Bella Aurora''.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=15698|page=565|date=1 May 1804}}</ref>\n\nShepheard commanded ''Pigmy'' until January 1803. He then transferred to take command of {{HMS|Basilisk|1801|2}}. His replacement was [[Martin White (Royal Navy officer)|Lieutenant Martin White]], who sailed ''Pigmy'' on the Guernsey station.<ref>''Naval Chronicle'', Vol. 9, p.79.</ref> White resigned his command of ''Pigmy'' in consequence of ill health,<ref name=NC11>''Naval Chronicle'', Vol. 11, p.175.</ref> but in March 1804, White transferred to {{HMS|Queen|1769|2}}. His replacement on ''Pygmy'' was Lieutenant Samuel Burgess.<ref name=NC11/> Lieutenant William Smith replaced Burgess in 1805.{{sfnp|Winfield|2008|p=354}}\n\n==Fate==\nOn 10 August 1805 ''Pigmy'' was wrecked in [[Saint Aubin, Jersey]], but without loss of life. She was about an hour into her departure to start a cruise when she hit a rock. She was stuck on the rock and repeated attempts to free her were unsuccessful. As the tide ebbed yards were deployed to prevent her healing over, and anchors too with the intent of kedging her off once the tide returned. At the same time boats from other vessels came and took off her stores, guns, and ammunition. Lastly, her crew cut away her masts. As the tide returned it still proved impossible to free her and she started filling with water. Boats took off her crew and by 4pm she had disappeared beneath the water.{{sfnp|Hepper|1994|p=112}}\n\nThe court martial of Smith, his officers, and crew took place in Portsmouth ten days later. The court martial board reprimanded the pilot, but honourably acquitted Smith, his officers, and crew.<ref>''Naval Chronicle'', Vol. 14, p.173.</ref>\n\n==Notes, citations, and references==\n===Notes===\n{{reflist|group=Note}}\n===Citations===\n{{reflist|30em}}\n===References===\n* {{cite book| last = Demerliac| first = Alain| title = La Marine de Louis XVI: nomenclature des navires fran\u00e7ais de 1774 \u00e0 1792| year = 1996| isbn = 978-2-906381-23-0 }}\n*{{cite book|last=Hepper|first=David J.|authorlink=|year=1994|title=British Warship Losses in the Age of Sail, 1650-1859|publisher=Jean Boudriot|location=Rotherfield|isbn=0-948864-30-3}}\n* {{cite book| last = Roche| first = Jean-Michel| title = Dictionnaire des b\u00e2timents de la flotte de guerre fran\u00e7aise de Colbert \u00e0 nos jours| volume = 1| year = 2005| publisher = Group Retozel-Maury Millau| isbn = 978-2-9525917-0-6| oclc = 165892922| page = 319 }}\n* {{cite book | last = Winfield| first = Rif|title = British Warships of the Age of Sail 1714\u20131792: Design, Construction, Careers and Fates | publisher =  Seaforth| year = 2007|isbn=9781844157006}}\n*{{cite book |first=Rif|last=Winfield|title=British Warships in the Age of Sail 1793&ndash;1817: Design, Construction, Careers and Fates|publisher=Seaforth|year=2008|isbn=1861762461}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mutin (1778)}}\n[[Category:1778 ships]]\n[[Category:Captured ships]]\n[[Category:Cutters of the Royal Navy]]\n", "text_old": "{{other ships|French ship Mutin|HMS Mutine|HMS Pigmy}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2017}}\n{|{{Infobox ship begin}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n|Ship image=\n|Ship caption=\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n|Hide header=\n|Ship country=France\n|Ship flag=[[File:Flag of the Kingdom of France (1814-1830).svg|45px|border|French Navy Ensign]] \n|Ship name=''Mutin''\n|Ship namesake=\n|Ship ordered=\n|Ship builder=Dunkirk\n|Ship laid down=June 1778\n|Ship launched=November 1778\n|Ship acquired=\n|Ship commissioned=\n|Ship decommissioned=\n|Ship in service=\n|Ship out of service=\n|Ship captured=2 October 1779\n|Ship struck=\n|Ship reinstated=\n|Ship fate=\n|Ship status=\n|Ship honours=\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n|Hide header=title\n|Ship country=[[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland|UK]]\n|Ship flag=[[File:Naval Ensign of the United Kingdom.svg|60px|Royal Navy Ensign]]\n|Ship name=HMS ''Mutine''\n|Ship ordered=\n|Ship builder=\n|Ship laid down=\n|Ship launched=\n|Ship acquired=2 October 1779 by capture\n|Ship commissioned=\n|Ship decommissioned=\n|Ship in service=\n|Ship out of service=\n|Ship renamed=HMS ''Pigmy'' 20 January 1798\n|Ship struck=\n|Ship reinstated=\n|Ship honours=[[Naval General Service Medal (1847)|Naval General Service Medal]] with clasp \"Egypt\"<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=21077|pages=791\u2013792|date=15 March 1850}}</ref>\n|Ship captured=\n|Ship fate=Wrecked 10&nbsp;August&nbsp;1805\n|Ship status=\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n|Hide header=\n|Header caption={{sfnp|Winfield|2008|p=354}} \n|Ship class=[[Mutin class cutter|''Mutin''-class cutter]]\n|Ship type=[[Cutter (ship)|Cutter]]\n|Ship tonnage=\n|Ship displacement=\n|Ship tons burthen=215{{small|{{frac|9|94}}}} ([[Builder's Old Measurement|bm]])\n|Ship length=*Overall:{{convert|76|ft|11+1/4|in|m|1|abbr=on}} \n*Keel:{{convert|59|ft|5+1/4|in|m|1|abbr=on}}\n|Ship beam={{convert|26|ft|1|in|m|1|abbr=on}}\n|Ship height=\n|Ship draught=\n|Ship hold depth={{convert|10|ft|1|in|m|1|abbr=on}}\n|Ship sail plan=\n|Ship speed=\n|Ship endurance=\n|Ship boats=\n|Ship capacity=\n|Ship troops=\n|Ship complement=*French service: 84 (but 120 at capture)\n*British service:70\n|Ship crew=\n|Ship armament=*French service: 14 guns\n*British service: 14 x 4-pounder guns + 10 x \u00bd-pounder [[swivel gun]]s\n|Ship armour=\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n|}\n'''''Mutin''''' was a 14-gun [[Cutter (ship)|cutter]] of the [[French Navy]], the lead ship of the [[Mutin-class cutter|''Mutin'' Class]] of five naval cutters. She was launched in 1778 and the [[Royal Navy]] captured her the next year, taking her into service as HMS ''Mutine''. The Royal Navy renamed her HMS ''Pigmy'' in 1798. She was lost in 1805.\n\n== Career ==\nOn 17 August 1779 ''Mutin'' accepted the surrender of the British cutter {{HMS|Active|1779|2}} in the Channel. ''Active'' had encountered the combined Franco-Spanish fleet in the [[English Channel]] and was unable to escape.{{sfnp|Hepper|1994|p=56}}\n\n[[HMS Jupiter (1778)|HMS ''Jupiter'']] captured ''Mutin'', along with her sister [[French ship Pilote (1779)|''Pilote'']], on 2 October after having dismasted ''Mutin'' by gunfire.{{sfnp|Demerliac|1996|p=87, #574}} At the time of her capture ''Mutin'' was under the command of Chevalier de Roquefieul.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=12020|page=2|date=5 October 1779}}</ref>\n\n===Royal Navy service===\nBetween 16 November 1779 and 13 December 1780, she was at Portsmouth, being fitted. The Royal Navy named and registered her as HMS ''Mutine'' on 22 January 1780.{{sfnp|Winfield|2008|p=354}} Lieutenant Samuel Cox commissioned her in October 1779 for the North Sea.\n\n''Mutine'' shared with His Majesty's cutters {{HMS|Rambler|1778|2}} and {{HMS|Griffin|1778|2}} in the capture on 30 December 1780 of the French privateer ''General Ville Pateaux''.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=12171|page=2|date=17 March 1781}}</ref>\n\nFrom March 1782 she was under the command of Lieutenant James Hills. On 6 October she captured the French privateer [[lugger]]  ''Compte de Valentinois'' and delivered it to Admiralty control at Spithead.<ref>{{cite news| title =Captures By British men of war | work =The Scots Magazine | page =52 | publisher = | date =1 December 1782 | url =http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/BL/0000545/17821201/012/0052?browse=true | accessdate =1 November 2015 }}</ref> ''Count de Valentinois'' was armed with two 3-pounder guns and eight swivel guns. She had a crew of 31 men under the command of Captain Le Dos and had sailed from Cherbourg the previous evening. She had captured nothing prior to encountering ''Mutine''.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=12378|page=1|date=8 October 1782}}</ref> \n\nIn May 1783 Lieutenant Robert Watson replaced Hills. Watson remained in command until ''Mutine'' was [[paid off]] in 1787 and transferred to [[Plymouth Dockyard]] for repairs. There was no work on the ship until 1789, when she underwent an extensive refit at a cost of \u00a33,884.{{sfnp|Winfield|2007|p=336}}{{refn|This equates to a relative value of \u00a3426,400 in 2014 terms.<ref>{{cite web| title =Purchasing Power of British Pounds from 1264 to Present | publisher =MeasuringWorth | date=2015 | url =http://www.measuringworth.com/ukcompare/result.php?year_source=1789&amount=3884&year_result=2014| accessdate =1 November 2015}}</ref>|group=Note}} \n\n''Mutine'' was recommissioned in October 1789 under Lieutenant Humphrey West and detailed for Mediterranean service in 1790. From July 1795 she was assigned to the squadron led by Admiral [[Horatio Nelson]], then in position off the coast of Genoa.{{sfnp|Winfield|2007|p=336}}\n\n===French Revolutionary Wars===\nIn January 1797 Lieutenant William Shepheard replaced West. ''Mutine'' was renamed ''Pigmy'' in 1798. She shared with {{HMS|Arethusa|1793|2}}, {{HMS|Netley|1798|2}} and the cutter {{HMS|Trial|1793|2}} in the proceeds from the detention of two vessels under neutral colours, ''Federick Molk'' and ''Vrow Judith'', on 18 and 21 August.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=15487|page=601|date=8 June 1802}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 January 1799, at noon, ''Pigmy'' was two miles SE of [[Durlston Bay|Durlston Head]] when she sighted a cutter and two brigs. ''Pigmy'' gave chase and at 1:40 succeeded in recapturing the two brigs, ''Lark'' and ''Dion''. After securing these two vessels ''Pigmy'' continued the chase with the result that at 4pm she succeeded in capturing the French privateer cutter ''Rancune''. ''Rancune'' was armed with two [[swivel gun]]s and had a crew of 21 men under the command of Antoine Fran\u00e7ois Victor Joseph Panpeville. She was 26 hours out of Cherbourg and the two brigs were her sole captures. ''Lark'', Francis Artis, master, was sailing from Cardiff to London with a cargo of bar iron. ''Dion'', Esdras Best, master, was on the same route and with the same cargo.captured the French privateer ''Rancune''.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=15097|pages=36\u201337||date=9 January 1799}}</ref>  For the remainder of the year, ''Pygmy'' operated in [[Quiberon Bay]] supporting the Royalist by bringing arms and money.<ref name=Marshall>Marshall (1829), Supplement, Part 3, pp.21-23.</ref>\n\n''Pigmy'' shared with {{HMS|Anson|1781|2}}, {{HMS|Boadicea|1797|2}}, {{HMS|Severn|1786|2}}, and {{HMS|Sheerness|1787|2}}, and the [[hired armed vessels|hired armed]] cutter [[Hired armed cutter Telemachus|''Telemachus'']] in the capture of four vessels:<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=15301|page=1176|date=11 October 1800}}</ref>\n*''St Francois'', taken 25 December 1799;\n*''St Pierre de Carnac'', taken 12 January 1800;\n*a brig of unknown name, taken 17 January 1800; and\n*''Anna Louisa'', taken 22 January 1800.\n\nIn May 1800 ''Pigmy'' was part of the Royal Navy squadron assisting at the [[Siege of Genoa (1800)|siege of Genoa]]. She shared with numerous other British vessels in the proceeds of the row galley cut out by their boats on 21 May,<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=15821|page=869|date=2 July 1805}}</ref> the capture on 23 May of the ''St Jean Baptiste'',<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=15820|page=851|date=29 June 1805}}</ref> the capture of the ketch [[French brig Albanaise (1790)|''Albanaise'']] on 4 June that the Royal Navy took into service, and the surrender of the city that same day.<ref>{{London Gazette|date=16 July 1805|issue=15825|page=933}}</ref>{{refn|A petty officer's share of the prize money for ''Albanaise'' was worth 7[[shilling|s]] 4[[pence|d]]; a seaman's share was worth 1s 3d. There was also an allocation of prize money for sundry vessels carrying corn that came into Genoa between 4 and 16 June. A petty officer's share of the prize money was worth 3s 6d; a seaman's share was worth 8d.<ref>{{London Gazette|date=11 April 1809|issue=16246|page=505}}</ref>|group=Note}}\n\nOn 20 July 1800, ''Pigmy'' was in company {{HMS|Speedy|1782|2}}, under the command of [[Thomas Cochrane, 10th Earl of Dundonald|Lord Cochrane]], in the Mediterranean. They captured the Imperial [[tartane]] ''Madonna Moseti Petro'', which was sailing to Cabrera with a cargo of wood.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=15301|page=1170|date=11 October 1800}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 August 1800, the brig {{HMS|Corso|1796|2}}, Lieutenant W. Ricketts, commander, and  ''Pigmy'' were at [[Cesenatico]]. Their orders were to destroy the vessels in its harbour, and \"make a proper example of the town.\" The British were unable to approach closely enough so during the night of 30 August Ricketts sent in boats of both vessels under the overall command of Lieutenant [[James Lucas Yeo]], first lieutenant of ''Corso''. The attackers were able to capture the town, sink two boats, and burn 11 others. One of the sunken vessels was deeply laden with copper, money, and bale goods. Four of the vessels sank in the mouth of the harbour, and fire consumed both piers. The British sailors were able to hold off some French infantry, but when Ricketts observed French cavalry approaching he ordered the boats to withdraw.<ref name=LG15301>{{London Gazette|issue=15301|pages=1171\u20131172|date=11 October 1800}}</ref>\n\nAfterwards, Ricketts sent the authorities of the town the following note:<ref name=LG15301/>\n<blockquote>To the Inhabitants of Cesenatico.\nThe Treachery of your Municipality, in causing to be arrested an Officer with Dispatches, has been long known to the British Admiral in these Seas. That Municipality may now sadly know that the Severity of Judgment, long delayed, is always exemplary. That the Innocent suffer with the Guilty, though much to be regretted, is the natural Feature of War; and the more terrible Infliction on this occasion, the more striking the Example should prove to surrounding Municipalities.\n(Signed) W. RICKETTS</blockquote>\n\nFrom September 1800 to June 1801, ''Pygmy'', alone or with ''Corso'', captured several small vessels, some of them armed:<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=15428|pages=1383\u20131386|date=17 November 1801}}</ref>\n\n*French [[trabaccolo]] privateer ''Bataglia di Marengo'', while on a cruise from [[Ravenna]] (6 September);\n*Imperial trabaccalo ''Divine Providence'', sailing from Cesenatriro to France with a cargo of rope (17 September);\n*Neapolitan [[polacca]] brig ''Madona de Laura'', sailing from Trepano to Ponto Gai with a cargo of salt (20 September);\n*Imperial trabaccolo ''Divine Providence'', sailing from [[Monopoli]] to Milan with a cargo of oil (6 October);\n*Cisalpine trabaccolo sailing from Ravenna to [[Pesaro]] with a cargo of oil (16 November, with ''Corso'');   \n*Cisalpine trabacolo, from Ravenna bound to Pesaro, in ballast (16 November, with ''Corso'');\n*Imperial ship ''Seinge'', sailing from Barcelona to Trieste with a cargo of brandy (17 January 1801, with ''Corso'');\n*Russian polacca ship ''Madona Turgliana'', sailing from the Morea to Trieste with a cargo of leather (17 January, with ''Corso'');{{refn|''Seinge'' is probably ''Strange'', which ''Corso'' captured that day.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=15506|page=861|date=14 August 1802}}</ref>|group=Note}}\n*Danish ship ''Adonis'', detained while sailing from Copenhagen to Trieste with a cargo of stockfish (13 February, with ''Corso'');\n*Danish brig ''Madellina Christiana'', detained while sailing from Venice to [[Zante]] with a cargo of planks (16 February, with ''Corso'');\n*French trabaccolo ''Ad\u00e9la\u00efde'' (see below);\n*Imperial trabaccolo ''Madona del Anunciade'', sailing from Trieste to Fiume with a cargo of hemp (27 February, with ''Corso'');\n*French trabaccolo privateer ''Achille'' (15 March, see below, with ''Corso''); and\n*French brig ''Prudente'', of two guns and 36 men, sailing from Toulon to Alexandria, with a cargo of ammunition, artificers' tools, and \"Comedians\" (8  June).(Apparently ''Prudente'' had some 100 passengers aboard, including troops, and actual comedians.)<ref name=Marshall/>\n\nThe deputies of the Mercantile Insurance Company in Trieste presented Shepheard with a golden snuffbox on 5 January as an expression of their appreciation for his efforts in suppressing \"piratical enemies\" in the upper Adriatic.<ref name=Marshall/>\n\nOn 18 February 1801, ''Pigmy'' captured the French privateer ''Ad\u00e9la\u00efde''. ''Ad\u00e9la\u00efde'' had been a fishing trabaccolo before her conversion to privateer. She was armed with one 6-pounder and two 12-pounder guns, and had a crew of 51 men under the command of Dominique Cannilla. She was seven days out of Ancona and had taken one small prize.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=15350|page=362|date=31 March 1801}}</ref> On 26 February ''Pigmy'' captured the ''Madona Turliana''.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=16192|page=1416|date=15 October 1808}}</ref>\n\nThen on the morning of 16 March ''Pigmy'' was on the north side of \"Isle Lonzo'\" when she sighted and gave chase to another trabaccolo. About two hours later this vessel anchored near the \"Isle Molata\", hoisted French colours, fired one shot, and then [[striking the colours|struck]]. She proved to be the privateer ''Achille'', of four 9-pounder and two brass 6-pounder guns. She had a crew of 44 men and was one day out of Ancona. She had not taken any prizes.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=15359|page=465|date=28 April 1801}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 April ''Corso'' and ''Pigmy'' captured the ''St Luigi''.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=16180|page=1233|date=6 September 1808}}</ref>\n\n''Pigmy'' was among the many vessels that shared in the proceeds of the capture on 9 June of the ''Felicit\u00e9'' and ''Josephine'' off Alexandria.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=15929|page=772|date=27 June 1806}}</ref>\n\nThe next day, ''Pigmy'' spoke with {{HMS|Swiftsure|1787|2}} and warned Captain [[Benjamin Hallowell Carew|Benjamin Hallowell]] that a French squadron under Admiral [[Honor\u00e9 Joseph Antoine Ganteaume|Ganteaume]] had put to sea. ''Swiftsure'' and the French encountered each other on 24 June, with the result that ''Swiftsure'' was forced to strike.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=15437|pages=1505\u20131506|date=19 December 1801}}</ref>\n\n{{main|Action of 24 June 1801}}\n\nBecause ''Pigmy'' served in the navy's Egyptian campaign between 8 March and 2 September, her officers and crew qualified for the clasp \"Egypt\" to the Naval General Service Medal that the [[Admiralty]] authorised in 1850 for all surviving claimants.{{#tag:ref|A first-class share of the prize money awarded in April 1823 was worth [[\u00a3sd|\u00a3]]34 2[[shilling|s]] 4[[pence|d]]; a fifth-class share, that of a seaman, was worth 3s 11\u00bdd. The amount was small as the total had to be shared between 79 vessels and the entire army contingent.<ref>{{London Gazette|page=633 |issue=17915|date=3 April 1823}}</ref>|group=Note}}\n\nOn 18 September, ''Pigmy'' captured the Ottoman polacca ''St Michele''.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=15533|page=1214|date=16 November 1802}}</ref> ''Pigmy'' shared with {{HMS|Pomone|1794|2}}, {{HMS|Vincejo|1799|2}}, and the privateer ''Furioso'' in the proceeds of the capture on 2 October of the ''Bella Aurora''.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=15698|page=565|date=1 May 1804}}</ref>\n\nShepheard commanded ''Pigmy'' until January 1803. He then transferred to take command of {{HMS|Basilisk|1801|2}}. His replacement was [[Martin White (Royal Navy officer)|Lieutenant Martin White]], who sailed ''Pigmy'' on the Guernsey station.<ref>''Naval Chronicle'', Vol. 9, p.79.</ref> White resigned his command of ''Pigmy'' in consequence of ill health,<ref name=NC11>''Naval Chronicle'', Vol. 11, p.175.</ref> but in March 1804, White transferred to {{HMS|Queen|1769|2}}. His replacement on ''Pygmy'' was Lieutenant Samuel Burgess.<ref name=NC11/> Lieutenant William Smith replaced Burgess in 1805.{{sfnp|Winfield|2008|p=354}}\n\n==Fate==\nOn 10 August 1805 ''Pigmy'' was wrecked in [[Saint Aubin, Jersey]], but without loss of life. She was about an hour into her departure to start a cruise when she hit a rock. She was stuck on the rock and repeated attempts to free her were unsuccessful. As the tide ebbed yards were deployed to prevent her healing over, and anchors too with the intent of kedging her off once the tide returned. At the same time boats from other vessels came and took off her stores, guns, and ammunition. Lastly, her crew cut away her masts. As the tide returned it still proved impossible to free her and she started filling with water. Boats took off her crew and by 4pm she had disappeared beneath the water.{{sfnp|Hepper|1994|p=112}}\n\nThe court martial of Smith, his officers, and crew took place in Portsmouth ten days later. The court martial board reprimanded the pilot, but honourably acquitted Smith, his officers, and crew.<ref>''Naval Chronicle'', Vol. 14, p.173.</ref>\n\n==Notes, citations, and references==\n===Notes===\n{{reflist|group=Note}}\n===Citations===\n{{reflist|30em}}\n===References===\n* {{cite book| last = Demerliac| first = Alain| title = La Marine de Louis XVI: nomenclature des navires fran\u00e7ais de 1774 \u00e0 1792| year = 1996| isbn = 978-2-906381-23-0 }}\n*{{cite book|last=Hepper|first=David J.|authorlink=|year=1994|title=British Warship Losses in the Age of Sail, 1650-1859|publisher=Jean Boudriot|location=Rotherfield|isbn=0-948864-30-3}}\n* {{cite book| last = Roche| first = Jean-Michel| title = Dictionnaire des b\u00e2timents de la flotte de guerre fran\u00e7aise de Colbert \u00e0 nos jours| volume = 1| year = 2005| publisher = Group Retozel-Maury Millau| isbn = 978-2-9525917-0-6| oclc = 165892922| page = 319 }}\n* {{cite book | last = Winfield| first = Rif|title = British Warships of the Age of Sail 1714\u20131792: Design, Construction, Careers and Fates | publisher =  Seaforth| year = 2007|isbn=9781844157006}}\n*{{cite book |first=Rif|last=Winfield|title=British Warships in the Age of Sail 1793&ndash;1817: Design, Construction, Careers and Fates|publisher=Seaforth|year=2008|isbn=1861762461}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mutin (1778)}}\n[[Category:1778 ships]]\n[[Category:Captured ships]]\n[[Category:Cutters of the Royal Navy]]\n", "name_user": "Mdnavman", "label": "safe", "comment": "Clean-up.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/French_cutter_Mutin_(1778)"}
{"title_page": "Patrick Jones", "text_new": "{{other people}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{EngvarB|date=January 2020}}\n{{BLP sources|date=December 2016}}\n\n{{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] -->\n| name         = Patrick Jones\n| birth_date   = {{birth year and age|1965}}\n| birth_place  = [[Tredegar]], [[Monmouthshire (historic)|Monmouthshire]], United Kingdom\n| occupation   = Poet, playwright, filmmaker\n| period       = 1986\u2013present\n| website      = {{url|patrick-jones.info}}\nGoals Scored = 69\n\n'''Patrick Jones''' (born 1899) is a proffesional choc player. playwright and senior sibling of Chistan.\n\n==Biography==\nBorn in [[Tredegar]] in 1965, Patrick Jones was educated at [[Oakdale, Caerphilly|Oakdale]] Comprehensive, [[Crosskeys College]] (a campus of [[Coleg Gwent]]), and then at the [[University of Wales, Swansea]] from 1983 to 1987. He was awarded Bsc. (Hons) in Sociology and American Studies. Jones has been employed in youth work, nursing aid, as a Literacy Officer and a Lecturer. He has lived much of his life in [[Blackwood, Caerphilly|Blackwood]] but has also lived in Herne Bay, [[Swansea]], in Germany, and spent four years in Chicago, Illinois.\n\nJones set up the Blackwood Young Writers Group based at the Blackwood Miners Institute in 1993. He taught Adult Literacy at Blackwood Community College and the Ebbw Vale Institute. Jones is also active in setting up various reading and writing workshops throughout Wales from schools to youth centres. He has also served as the Creative Literacy Worker for the Cynon Project and in 1988 was writer in residence at [[Swansea College]]. He has worked in collaboration with Hafan Cymru, Ty Hapus, Literature Wales and The Welsh National Opera.\n\nJones has made various television and radio appearances, and is probably Wales' most prominent living literary figure.{{citation needed|date=June 2018}} He participated in a week-long intensive writing masterclass with Arnold Wesker at [[Hay on Wye]] Literature Festival in 1997. Jones participated in the 1998 Dysfluency Tour. In April 1999, he staged a Kosovo benefit at Blackwood Miner's Institute involving [[Max Boyce]], [[James Dean Bradfield]] and other artists. Later that year he read from and discussed sections of his play ''Everything Must Go'' at Marxism '99. 1999 also saw Ioan Gruffydd, Matthew Rhys and other Welsh celebrities performing his poem \"The Guerrilla Tapestry\" at the opening of the [[Welsh Assembly]] 'Voices of a Nation' concert. In 2004, he returned to the [[Hay Festival]] for a discussion with James Dean Bradfield on music, politics and writing.\n\nJones has worked with St David's Foundation Hospice Care, The Samaritans, [[Hope and Aid Direct]] and Learning through Growth in the [[Cynon Valley]].. Has been involved in many protests including Save St David's Woods, and Justice for Fathers.  In 2007 he performed a reading at a fundraising concert for Stop The War, during which he also collaborated with Newport band New State Radio.\n\nJones' play, ''Revelation'', spoke out on behalf of victims of female domestic violence. Jones spent some time researching the play and it is based on over forty interviews with men who have experienced domestic violence.\n\nIt was supported by the Dyn Project Cardiff, Mankind UK, Chapter Arts Centre and the Welsh Arts Council. It was directed by Chris Durnall with Nathan Sussex and Stacey Daly and featured a soundtrack by Jones' friend and collaborator, James Dean Bradfield. It was performed at Chapter Arts Centre in July 2008 before transferring to a three-week run at the Courtyard Theatre in London as well as other, non-theatre venues.\n\nIn November 2008, [[Waterstone's]] cancelled an appearance from Jones at one of their stores, where he was expected to sign autographs and promote his new work, because of a planned protest by a religious pressure group over alleged [[blasphemy]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pinknews.co.uk/news/articles/2005-9573.html|title=Waterstone's give in to hate preacher Stephen Green as he threatens more artists}}</ref> In an effort to ensure that he was not gagged, Liberal Democrat Assembly Member [[Peter Black (Welsh politician)|Peter Black]] then asked Jones to read from his book, ''Darkness Is Where The Stars Are'', at the [[Welsh Assembly]], and the reading went ahead on 11 December despite protests.<ref name=\"assembly\">[http://www.walesonline.co.uk/news/south-wales-news/blaenau-gwent/2008/12/18/headyheady-91466-22486648/ Headyheady], [[Gwent Gazette]], 18 December 2008</ref>\n\nA CD ''Tongues for a Stammering Time'', with spoken word in collaboration with many musicians including Nicky Wire, James Dean Bradfield, [[Billy Bragg]], [[Amy Wadge]], [[Martyn Joseph]] and others, was released on [[Anhrefn Records]] in May 2009.\n\nIn 2014 ''The Forgotten'', a Chartist musical co written with Drama lecturer Vanessa Dodd was performed at The Riverfront and other venues in the South Wales are to mark the 175th anniversary of The Chartist Rising. In March 2015 it was announced that Jones' play ''Before I leave'' would be part of the National Theatre of Wales' 5th Year programme. The play was inspired by The Cwm Taf Choir based in Merthyr Tydfil which is supported by The Alzheimer's Society.\n\nJones worked with Rhiannon White Co Artistic Director of Common Wealth Theatre Company Summer 2015 in and around Blackwood, researching and developing his first play ''Everything Must Go'' which was resurrected for the second Velvet Coalmine festival.\n2016 saw the premiere of his new play Before I Leave produced by The National Theatre Wales. Based on research Jones undertook with various Dementia choirs and supported by The Alzheimer's Society Cymru, the play tells the story of a choir made up of members who live with dementia. It is currently being developed into a film.\n\nRough Trade Books published a new collection of poetry 'My Bright Shadow' in May 2019.  Written during his mother's battle with Leukaemia and after her death the work deals with grief, loss, healing and the power of words to bear witness to a life.\n\nA new album, Renegade Psalms was released in 2019. It is a collaboration with Jones and The Membranes singer and bassist John Robb, and featured eleven brand new tracks. A state of the nation address focusing on such issues as Brexit, austerity, the bedroom tax, housing inequality alongside hope, protest and love.\n\n== Works ==\n\n=== Books ===\n* ''The Guerrilla Tapestry'' (1995)\n* ''The Protest of Discipline'' (1996)\n* ''Detritus'' (1997)\n* ''Mute Communion'' (1997)\n* ''Fuse'' (Parthian Books) (2001) Includes a foreword by Nicky Wire called 'The Words are Coming'\n* ''Against'' (2003)\n* ''Last wRites (editor)'' (2006)\n* ''Darkness is where the stars are'' (2008)\n* 'The Aspirations of Poverty' Red Poets (2016)\n*  \"My Bright Shadow\" Rough Trade Books (2019)\n\n===Music videos===\nAll music videos are for Manic Street Preachers, using '[[Crash Editing]]' facilities.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!  Year !! Title !! Album\n|-\n||2003 |||Judge Yr'self |||[[Lipstick Traces (A Secret History of Manic Street Preachers)]]\n|-\n| rowspan=\"8\"|2004 |||1985||rowspan=\"6\"|[[Lifeblood (album)|Lifeblood]]\n|-\n||A Song For Departure\n|-\n||Cardiff Afterlife\n|-\n||Emily\n|-\n||Fragments\n|-\n||Solitude Sometimes Is\n|-\n||Quarantine (In My Place Of) \u2013 Short Film  |||B-side to the single [[The Love of Richard Nixon]]\n|-\n||Yes (New Film)|||[[The Holy Bible (album)|The Holy Bible (Tenth Anniversary Edition)]]\n|-\n||2005|||Firefight|||[[God Save The Manics EP]]\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|2006|||Further Away|| rowspan=\"2\"|[[Everything Must Go (Manic Street Preachers album)|Everything Must Go (Tenth Anniversary Edition)]]\n|-\n||Home Movie ''(footage, not music)'' \n|-\n||2007 |||[[Indian Summer (Manic Street Preachers song)|Indian Summer]] ||rowspan=\"2\"|[[Send Away The Tigers]]\n|-\n||2008 |||Send Away The Tigers\n|}\n\n{{Col-begin}}\n{{Col-break}}\n\n===Plays===\n* Everything Must Go (1999)\n* Unprotected Sex (1999)\n* The War Is Dead Long Live The War (2003)\n* Bridges (2006)\n* Sing To Me (2006)\n* Revelation (2008)\n* A Lament for Moths (2009)\n* Before I Leave (2016)\n{{Col-break}}\n\n===Short films===\n* Pictures of the Gone World (1999)\n* The Absence (2004)\n* Nutters (2007)\n\n===Other publications===\n* ''Commemoration and Amnesia'' (Big Noise Productions) (1999) (Poetry performed by bands)\n* ''Tongues for a Stammering Time'' (Anhrefn Records) (2009) (Poetry performed by bands)\n{{col-end}}\n* \"Renegade Psalms\" (Louder Than War ) in collaboration with John Robb\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*http://www.patrick-jones.info\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jones, Patrick}}\n[[Category:1965 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Tredegar]]\n[[Category:Welsh republicans]]\n[[Category:Welsh poets]]\n[[Category:Welsh dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:Anglo-Welsh poets]]\n[[Category:People educated at Oakdale Comprehensive School]]\n[[Category:21st-century Welsh poets]]\n[[Category:21st-century British male writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Welsh writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{other people}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{EngvarB|date=January 2020}}\n{{BLP sources|date=December 2016}}\n\n{{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] -->\n| name         = Patrick Jones\n| birth_date   = {{birth year and age|1965}}\n| birth_place  = [[Tredegar]], [[Monmouthshire (historic)|Monmouthshire]], United Kingdom\n| occupation   = Poet, playwright, filmmaker\n| period       = 1986\u2013present\n| website      = {{url|patrick-jones.info}}\n}}\n\n'''Patrick Jones''' (born 1965) is a Welsh poet, playwright and senior sibling of [[Nicky Wire]] of the [[Manic Street Preachers]].\n\n==Biography==\nBorn in [[Tredegar]] in 1965, Patrick Jones was educated at [[Oakdale, Caerphilly|Oakdale]] Comprehensive, [[Crosskeys College]] (a campus of [[Coleg Gwent]]), and then at the [[University of Wales, Swansea]] from 1983 to 1987. He was awarded Bsc. (Hons) in Sociology and American Studies. Jones has been employed in youth work, nursing aid, as a Literacy Officer and a Lecturer. He has lived much of his life in [[Blackwood, Caerphilly|Blackwood]] but has also lived in Herne Bay, [[Swansea]], in Germany, and spent four years in Chicago, Illinois.\n\nJones set up the Blackwood Young Writers Group based at the Blackwood Miners Institute in 1993. He taught Adult Literacy at Blackwood Community College and the Ebbw Vale Institute. Jones is also active in setting up various reading and writing workshops throughout Wales from schools to youth centres. He has also served as the Creative Literacy Worker for the Cynon Project and in 1988 was writer in residence at [[Swansea College]]. He has worked in collaboration with Hafan Cymru, Ty Hapus, Literature Wales and The Welsh National Opera.\n\nJones has made various television and radio appearances, and is probably Wales' most prominent living literary figure.{{citation needed|date=June 2018}} He participated in a week-long intensive writing masterclass with Arnold Wesker at [[Hay on Wye]] Literature Festival in 1997. Jones participated in the 1998 Dysfluency Tour. In April 1999, he staged a Kosovo benefit at Blackwood Miner's Institute involving [[Max Boyce]], [[James Dean Bradfield]] and other artists. Later that year he read from and discussed sections of his play ''Everything Must Go'' at Marxism '99. 1999 also saw Ioan Gruffydd, Matthew Rhys and other Welsh celebrities performing his poem \"The Guerrilla Tapestry\" at the opening of the [[Welsh Assembly]] 'Voices of a Nation' concert. In 2004, he returned to the [[Hay Festival]] for a discussion with James Dean Bradfield on music, politics and writing.\n\nJones has worked with St David's Foundation Hospice Care, The Samaritans, [[Hope and Aid Direct]] and Learning through Growth in the [[Cynon Valley]].. Has been involved in many protests including Save St David's Woods, and Justice for Fathers.  In 2007 he performed a reading at a fundraising concert for Stop The War, during which he also collaborated with Newport band New State Radio.\n\nJones' play, ''Revelation'', spoke out on behalf of victims of female domestic violence. Jones spent some time researching the play and it is based on over forty interviews with men who have experienced domestic violence.\n\nIt was supported by the Dyn Project Cardiff, Mankind UK, Chapter Arts Centre and the Welsh Arts Council. It was directed by Chris Durnall with Nathan Sussex and Stacey Daly and featured a soundtrack by Jones' friend and collaborator, James Dean Bradfield. It was performed at Chapter Arts Centre in July 2008 before transferring to a three-week run at the Courtyard Theatre in London as well as other, non-theatre venues.\n\nIn November 2008, [[Waterstone's]] cancelled an appearance from Jones at one of their stores, where he was expected to sign autographs and promote his new work, because of a planned protest by a religious pressure group over alleged [[blasphemy]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pinknews.co.uk/news/articles/2005-9573.html|title=Waterstone's give in to hate preacher Stephen Green as he threatens more artists}}</ref> In an effort to ensure that he was not gagged, Liberal Democrat Assembly Member [[Peter Black (Welsh politician)|Peter Black]] then asked Jones to read from his book, ''Darkness Is Where The Stars Are'', at the [[Welsh Assembly]], and the reading went ahead on 11 December despite protests.<ref name=\"assembly\">[http://www.walesonline.co.uk/news/south-wales-news/blaenau-gwent/2008/12/18/headyheady-91466-22486648/ Headyheady], [[Gwent Gazette]], 18 December 2008</ref>\n\nA CD ''Tongues for a Stammering Time'', with spoken word in collaboration with many musicians including Nicky Wire, James Dean Bradfield, [[Billy Bragg]], [[Amy Wadge]], [[Martyn Joseph]] and others, was released on [[Anhrefn Records]] in May 2009.\n\nIn 2014 ''The Forgotten'', a Chartist musical co written with Drama lecturer Vanessa Dodd was performed at The Riverfront and other venues in the South Wales are to mark the 175th anniversary of The Chartist Rising. In March 2015 it was announced that Jones' play ''Before I leave'' would be part of the National Theatre of Wales' 5th Year programme. The play was inspired by The Cwm Taf Choir based in Merthyr Tydfil which is supported by The Alzheimer's Society.\n\nJones worked with Rhiannon White Co Artistic Director of Common Wealth Theatre Company Summer 2015 in and around Blackwood, researching and developing his first play ''Everything Must Go'' which was resurrected for the second Velvet Coalmine festival.\n2016 saw the premiere of his new play Before I Leave produced by The National Theatre Wales. Based on research Jones undertook with various Dementia choirs and supported by The Alzheimer's Society Cymru, the play tells the story of a choir made up of members who live with dementia. It is currently being developed into a film.\n\nRough Trade Books published a new collection of poetry 'My Bright Shadow' in May 2019.  Written during his mother's battle with Leukaemia and after her death the work deals with grief, loss, healing and the power of words to bear witness to a life.\n\nA new album, Renegade Psalms was released in 2019. It is a collaboration with Jones and The Membranes singer and bassist John Robb, and featured eleven brand new tracks. A state of the nation address focusing on such issues as Brexit, austerity, the bedroom tax, housing inequality alongside hope, protest and love.\n\n== Works ==\n\n=== Books ===\n* ''The Guerrilla Tapestry'' (1995)\n* ''The Protest of Discipline'' (1996)\n* ''Detritus'' (1997)\n* ''Mute Communion'' (1997)\n* ''Fuse'' (Parthian Books) (2001) Includes a foreword by Nicky Wire called 'The Words are Coming'\n* ''Against'' (2003)\n* ''Last wRites (editor)'' (2006)\n* ''Darkness is where the stars are'' (2008)\n* 'The Aspirations of Poverty' Red Poets (2016)\n*  \"My Bright Shadow\" Rough Trade Books (2019)\n\n===Music videos===\nAll music videos are for Manic Street Preachers, using '[[Crash Editing]]' facilities.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!  Year !! Title !! Album\n|-\n||2003 |||Judge Yr'self |||[[Lipstick Traces (A Secret History of Manic Street Preachers)]]\n|-\n| rowspan=\"8\"|2004 |||1985||rowspan=\"6\"|[[Lifeblood (album)|Lifeblood]]\n|-\n||A Song For Departure\n|-\n||Cardiff Afterlife\n|-\n||Emily\n|-\n||Fragments\n|-\n||Solitude Sometimes Is\n|-\n||Quarantine (In My Place Of) \u2013 Short Film  |||B-side to the single [[The Love of Richard Nixon]]\n|-\n||Yes (New Film)|||[[The Holy Bible (album)|The Holy Bible (Tenth Anniversary Edition)]]\n|-\n||2005|||Firefight|||[[God Save The Manics EP]]\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|2006|||Further Away|| rowspan=\"2\"|[[Everything Must Go (Manic Street Preachers album)|Everything Must Go (Tenth Anniversary Edition)]]\n|-\n||Home Movie ''(footage, not music)'' \n|-\n||2007 |||[[Indian Summer (Manic Street Preachers song)|Indian Summer]] ||rowspan=\"2\"|[[Send Away The Tigers]]\n|-\n||2008 |||Send Away The Tigers\n|}\n\n{{Col-begin}}\n{{Col-break}}\n\n===Plays===\n* Everything Must Go (1999)\n* Unprotected Sex (1999)\n* The War Is Dead Long Live The War (2003)\n* Bridges (2006)\n* Sing To Me (2006)\n* Revelation (2008)\n* A Lament for Moths (2009)\n* Before I Leave (2016)\n{{Col-break}}\n\n===Short films===\n* Pictures of the Gone World (1999)\n* The Absence (2004)\n* Nutters (2007)\n\n===Other publications===\n* ''Commemoration and Amnesia'' (Big Noise Productions) (1999) (Poetry performed by bands)\n* ''Tongues for a Stammering Time'' (Anhrefn Records) (2009) (Poetry performed by bands)\n{{col-end}}\n* \"Renegade Psalms\" (Louder Than War ) in collaboration with John Robb\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*http://www.patrick-jones.info\n\n